# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alderney
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] As of 2021, small farms, of which the vast majority are one hectare (about 2.5 acres) or smaller, produce about one-third of the world's food.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Moreover, five of every six farms in the world consist of fewer than 2 hectares (4.9 acres) and take up only around 12% of all agricultural land.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] In terms of total land use, large farms are dominant.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] While only 1% of all farms globally are greater than 50 hectares (120 acres), they encompass more than 70% of the world's farmland.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Further, nearly 40% of all global agricultural land is found on farms larger than 1,000 hectares (2,500 acres).
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Farms and farming greatly influence rural economics and greatly shape rural society, affecting both the direct agricultural workforce and broader businesses that support the farms and farming populations.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] The major agricultural products can be broadly grouped into foods, fibers, fuels, and raw materials (such as rubber and timber).
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Food classes include cereals (grains), vegetables, fruits, cooking oils, meat, milk, eggs, and fungi.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Global agricultural production amounts to approximately 11 billion tonnes of food, 32 million tonnes of natural fibers and 4 billion m3 of wood.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] However, around 14% of the world's food is lost from production before reaching the retail level.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Modern agronomy, plant breeding, agrochemicals such as pesticides and fertilizers, and technological developments have sharply increased crop yields, but also contributed to ecological and environmental damage.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Selective breeding and modern practices in animal husbandry have similarly increased the output of meat, but have raised concerns about animal welfare and environmental damage.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Environmental issues include contributions to climate change, depletion of aquifers, deforestation, antibiotic resistance, and other agricultural pollution.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Agriculture is both a cause of and sensitive to environmental degradation, such as biodiversity loss, desertification, soil degradation, and climate change, all of which can cause decreases in crop yield.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Genetically modified organisms are widely used, although some countries ban them.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] The word *agriculture* is a late Middle English adaptation of Latin *agricultūra*, from *ager* 'field' and *cultūra* 'cultivation' or 'growing'.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Agriculture is defined with varying scopes, in its broadest sense using natural resources to "produce commodities which maintain life, including food, fiber, forest products, horticultural crops, and their related services".
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Thus defined, it includes arable farming, horticulture, animal husbandry and forestry, but horticulture and forestry are in practice often excluded.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] It may also be broadly decomposed into **plant agriculture**, which concerns the cultivation of useful plants, and **animal agriculture**, the production of agricultural animals.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] While agriculture usually refers to human activities, other species have been cultivating crops for up to 60 million years, such as some ant (see agriculture in ants), termite and beetle.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] The development of agriculture enabled the human population to grow many times larger than could be sustained by hunting and gathering.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Agriculture began independently in different parts of the globe, and included a diverse range of taxa, in at least 11 separate centers of origin.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Wild grains were collected and eaten from at least 105,000 years ago.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] In the Paleolithic Levant, 23,000 years ago, cereals cultivation of emmer, barley, and oats has been observed near the sea of Galilee.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Rice was domesticated in China between 11,500 and 6200 BC with the earliest known cultivation from 5700 BC, followed by mung, soy and azuki beans.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Sheep were domesticated in Mesopotamia between 13,000 and 11,000 years ago.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Cattle were domesticated from the wild aurochs in the areas of modern Turkey and Pakistan some 10,500 years ago.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Pig production emerged in Eurasia, including Europe, East Asia and Southwest Asia, where wild boar were first domesticated about 10,500 years ago.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] In the Andes of South America, the potato was domesticated between 10,000 and 7,000 years ago, along with beans, coca, llamas, alpacas, and guinea pigs.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Sugarcane and some root vegetables were domesticated in New Guinea around 9,000 years ago.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Sorghum was domesticated in the Sahel region of Africa by 7,000 years ago.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Cotton was domesticated in Peru by 5,600 years ago, and was independently domesticated in Eurasia.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] In Mesoamerica, wild teosinte was bred into maize (corn) from 10,000 to 6,000 years ago.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] The horse was domesticated in the Eurasian Steppes around 3500 BC.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Scholars have offered multiple hypotheses to explain the historical origins of agriculture.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Studies of the transition from hunter-gatherer to agricultural societies indicate an initial period of intensification and increasing sedentism; examples are the Natufian culture in the Levant, and the Early Chinese Neolithic in China.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Then, wild stands that had previously been harvested started to be planted, and gradually came to be domesticated.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] In Eurasia, the Sumerians started to live in villages from about 8000 BC, relying on the Tigris and Euphrates rivers and a canal system for irrigation.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Ploughs appear in pictographs around 3000 BC; seed-ploughs around 2300 BC.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Farmers grew wheat, barley, vegetables such as lentils and onions, and fruits including dates, grapes, and figs.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Ancient Egyptian agriculture relied on the Nile River and its seasonal flooding.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Farming started in the predynastic period at the end of the Paleolithic, after 10,000 BC.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Staple food crops were grains such as wheat and barley, alongside industrial crops such as flax and papyrus.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] In India, wheat, barley and jujube were domesticated by 9000 BC, soon followed by sheep and goats.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Cattle, sheep and goats were domesticated in Mehrgarh culture by 8000–6000 BC.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Cotton was cultivated by the 5th–4th millennium BC.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Archeological evidence indicates an animal-drawn plough from 2500 BC in the Indus Valley civilization.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] In China, from the 5th century BC, there was a nationwide granary system and widespread silk farming.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Water-powered grain mills were in use by the 1st century BC, followed by irrigation.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] By the late 2nd century, heavy ploughs had been developed with iron ploughshares and mouldboards.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Asian rice was domesticated 8,200–13,500 years ago – depending on the molecular clock estimate that is used– on the Pearl River in southern China with a single genetic origin from the wild rice *Oryza rufipogon*.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] In Greece and Rome, the major cereals were wheat, emmer, and barley, alongside vegetables including peas, beans, and olives.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Sheep and goats were kept mainly for dairy products.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] In the Americas, crops domesticated in Mesoamerica (apart from teosinte) include squash, beans, and cacao.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Cocoa was domesticated by the Mayo Chinchipe of the upper Amazon around 3000 BC.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] The turkey was probably domesticated in Mexico or the American Southwest.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] The Aztecs developed irrigation systems, formed terraced hillsides, fertilized their soil, and developed chinampas or artificial islands.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] The Mayas used extensive canal and raised field systems to farm swampland from 400 BC.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] In South America agriculture may have begun about 9000 BC with the domestication of squash (Cucurbita) and other plants.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Coca was domesticated in the Andes, as were the peanut, tomato, tobacco, and pineapple.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Cotton was domesticated in Peru by 3600 BC.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Animals including llamas, alpacas, and guinea pigs were domesticated there.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] In North America, the indigenous people of the East domesticated crops such as sunflower, tobacco, squash and *Chenopodium*.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Wild foods including wild rice and maple sugar were harvested.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] The domesticated strawberry is a hybrid of a Chilean and a North American species, developed by breeding in Europe and North America.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] The indigenous people of the Southwest and the Pacific Northwest practiced forest gardening and fire-stick farming.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] The natives controlled fire on a regional scale to create a low-intensity fire ecology that sustained a low-density agriculture in loose rotation; a sort of "wild" permaculture.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] A system of companion planting called the Three Sisters was developed in North America.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] The three crops were winter squash, maize, and climbing beans.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Indigenous Australians, long supposed to have been nomadic hunter-gatherers, practiced systematic burning, possibly to enhance natural productivity in fire-stick farming.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Scholars have pointed out that hunter-gatherers need a productive environment to support gathering without cultivation.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Because the forests of New Guinea have few food plants, early humans may have used "selective burning" to increase the productivity of the wild karuka fruit trees to support the hunter-gatherer way of life.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] The Gunditjmara and other groups developed eel farming and fish trapping systems from some 5,000 years ago.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] There is evidence of 'intensification' across the whole continent over that period.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] In two regions of Australia, the central west coast and eastern central, early farmers cultivated yams, native millet, and bush onions, possibly in permanent settlements.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] In the Middle Ages, compared to the Roman period, agriculture in Western Europe became more focused on self-sufficiency.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] The agricultural population under feudalism was typically organized into manors consisting of several hundred or more acres of land presided over by a lord of the manor with a Roman Catholic church and priest.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Thanks to the exchange with the Al-Andalus where the Arab Agricultural Revolution was underway, European agriculture transformed, with improved techniques and the diffusion of crop plants, including the introduction of sugar, rice, cotton and fruit trees (such as the orange).
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] After 1492, the Columbian exchange brought New World crops such as maize, potatoes, tomatoes, sweet potatoes, and manioc to Europe, and Old World crops such as wheat, barley, rice, and turnips, and livestock (including horses, cattle, sheep and goats) to the Americas.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Irrigation, crop rotation, and fertilizers advanced from the 17th century with the British Agricultural Revolution, allowing global population to rise significantly.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Since 1900, agriculture in developed nations, and to a lesser extent in the developing world, has seen large rises in productivity as mechanization replaces human labor, and assisted by synthetic fertilizers, pesticides, and selective breeding.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] The Haber-Bosch method allowed the synthesis of ammonium nitrate fertilizer on an industrial scale, greatly increasing crop yields and sustaining a further increase in global population.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Pastoralism involves managing domesticated animals.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] In nomadic pastoralism, herds of livestock are moved from place to place in search of pasture, fodder, and water.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] This type of farming is practiced in arid and semi-arid regions of Sahara, Central Asia and some parts of India.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] In shifting cultivation, a small area of forest is cleared by cutting and burning the trees.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] The cleared land is used for growing crops for a few years until the soil becomes too infertile, and the area is abandoned.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Another patch of land is selected and the process is repeated.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] This type of farming is practiced mainly in areas with abundant rainfall where the forest regenerates quickly.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] This practice is used in Northeast India, Southeast Asia, and the Amazon Basin.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Subsistence farming is practiced to satisfy family or local needs alone, with little left over for transport elsewhere.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] It is intensively practiced in Monsoon Asia and South-East Asia.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] An estimated 2.5 billion subsistence farmers worked in 2018, cultivating about 60% of the earth's arable land.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Intensive farming is cultivation to maximize productivity, with a low fallow ratio and a high use of inputs (water, fertilizer, pesticide and automation).
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] It is practiced mainly in developed countries.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] From the twentieth century onwards, intensive agriculture increased crop productivity.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] It substituted synthetic fertilizers and pesticides for labor, but caused increased water pollution, and often involved farm subsidies.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Soil degradation and diseases such as stem rust are major concerns globally; approximately 40% of the world's agricultural land is seriously degraded.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Modern agriculture has raised or encountered ecological, political, and economic issues including water pollution, biofuels, genetically modified organisms, tariffs and farm subsidies, leading to alternative approaches such as the organic movement.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Unsustainable farming practices in North America led to the Dust Bowl of the 1930s.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] In recent years there has been a backlash against the environmental effects of conventional agriculture, resulting in the organic, regenerative, and sustainable agriculture movements.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] One of the major forces behind this movement has been the European Union, which first certified organic food in 1991 and began reform of its Common Agricultural Policy (CAP) in 2005 to phase out commodity-linked farm subsidies, also known as decoupling.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] The growth of organic farming has renewed research in alternative technologies such as integrated pest management, selective breeding, and controlled-environment agriculture.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] There are concerns about the lower yield associated with organic farming and its impact on global food security.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Recent mainstream technological developments include genetically modified food.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] During the 60-year period between 1964 and 2023, most of the increase in agricultural production was achieved through intensification, while the expansion of agricultural land was limited to just 8%.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] In the twenty-first century, between 2001 and 2023, global agricultural area decreased by 78 million hectares (Mha) (−2%), with cropland area increasing by 78 Mha and permanent meadows and pastures decreasing by 151 Mha.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] These changes exhibit significant regional variations.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Sub-Saharan Africa witnessed cropland expansion of 69 Mha accompanied by 72 Mha of forest loss, while Latin America saw 25 Mha of cropland growth alongside 85 Mha of net forest area loss.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Agricultural expansion remains the primary driver of global deforestation, accounting for nearly 90% of forest loss.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] In this century, another important aspect to consider is that approximately 3.6 Mha of croplands are abandoned annually, with land degradation likely playing a significant role in these losses.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] By 2015, the agricultural output of China was the largest in the world, followed by the European Union, India and the United States.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Economists measure the total factor productivity of agriculture, according to which agriculture in the United States is roughly 1.7 times more productive than it was in 1948.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Agriculture employed 873 million people in 2021, or 27% of the global workforce, 916 million in 2023, compared with 1 027 million (or 40%) in 2000.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] The share of agriculture in global GDP was stable at around 4% since 2000–2023.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Despite increases in agricultural production and productivity, between 702 and 828 million people were affected by hunger in 2021.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Food insecurity and malnutrition can be the result of conflict, climate extremes and variability and economic swings.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] It can also be caused by a country's structural characteristics such as income status and natural resource endowments as well as its political economy.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Pesticide use in agriculture went up 62% between 2000 and 2021, with the Americas accounting for half the use in 2021.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] The International Fund for Agricultural Development posits that an increase in smallholder agriculture may be part of the solution to concerns about food prices and overall food security, given the favorable experience of Vietnam.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Agriculture provides about one-quarter of all global employment, more than half in sub-Saharan Africa and almost 60 percent in low-income countries.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] As countries develop, other jobs have historically pulled workers away from agriculture, and labor-saving innovations increase agricultural productivity by reducing labor requirements per unit of output.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Over time, a combination of labor supply and labor demand trends have driven down the share of population employed in agriculture.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] During the 16th century in Europe, between 55 and 75% of the population was engaged in agriculture; by the 19th century, this had dropped to between 35 and 65%.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] In the same countries today, the figure is less than 10%.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] At the start of the 21st century, some one billion people, or over 1/3 of the available work force, were employed in agriculture.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] This constitutes approximately 70% of the global employment of children, and in many countries constitutes the largest percentage of women of any industry.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] The service sector overtook the agricultural sector as the largest global employer in 2007.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] In many developed countries, immigrants help fill labor shortages in high-value agriculture activities that are difficult to mechanize.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Foreign farm workers from mostly Eastern Europe, North Africa and South Asia constituted around one-third of the salaried agricultural workforce in Spain, Italy, Greece and Portugal in 2013.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Around the world, women make up a large share of the population employed in agriculture.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] This share is growing in all developing regions except East and Southeast Asia where women already make up about 50 percent of the agricultural workforce.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Women make up 47 percent of the agricultural workforce in sub-Saharan Africa, a rate that has not changed significantly in the past few decades.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Women who work in agricultural production tend to do so under highly unfavorable conditions.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] They tend to be concentrated in the poorest countries, where alternative livelihoods are not available, and they maintain the intensity of their work in conditions of climate-induced weather shocks and in situations of conflict.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Women are less likely to participate as entrepreneurs and independent farmers and are engaged in the production of less lucrative crops.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] The gender gap in land productivity between female- and male managed farms of the same size is 24 percent.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] On average, women earn 18.4 percent less than men in wage employment in agriculture; this means that women receive 82 cents for every dollar earned by men.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Progress has been slow in closing gaps in women's access to irrigation and in ownership of livestock, too.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Women in agriculture still have significantly less access than men to inputs, including improved seeds, fertilizers and mechanized equipment.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] On a positive note, the gender gap in access to mobile internet in low- and middle-income countries fell from 25 percent to 16 percent between 2017 and 2021, and the gender gap in access to bank accounts narrowed from 9 to 6 percentage points.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Women are as likely as men to adopt new technologies when the necessary enabling factors are put in place and they have equal access to complementary resources.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Agriculture, specifically farming, remains a hazardous industry, and farmers worldwide remain at high risk of work-related injuries, lung disease, noise-induced hearing loss, skin diseases, as well as certain cancers related to chemical use and prolonged sun exposure.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] On industrialized farms, injuries frequently involve the use of agricultural machinery, and a common cause of fatal agricultural injuries in developed countries is tractor rollovers.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Pesticides and other chemicals used in farming can be hazardous to worker health, and workers exposed to pesticides may experience illness or have children with birth defects.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] As an industry in which families commonly share in work and live on the farm itself, entire families can be at risk for injuries, illness, and death.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Ages 0–6 may be an especially vulnerable population in agriculture; common causes of fatal injuries among young farm workers include drowning, machinery and motor accidents, including with all-terrain vehicles.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Occupational fatality data from the last decade indicate that, when looking at all industries, agriculture had the leading number of work-related deaths for youth.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Within this industry, youth between the ages of 10 and 15 suffered the most non-fatal work-related injuries.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] While farming is hazardous, studies have looked at the fact that there are also many benefits to growing up and living on a farm.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] The International Labor Organization considers agriculture "one of the most hazardous of all economic sectors".
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] It estimates that the annual work-related death toll among agricultural employees is at least 170,000, twice the average rate of other jobs.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] In addition, incidences of death, injury and illness related to agricultural activities often go unreported.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] The organization has developed the Safety and Health in Agriculture Convention, 2001, which covers the range of risks in the agriculture occupation, the prevention of these risks and the role that individuals and organizations engaged in agriculture should play.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] In the United States, agriculture has been identified by the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health as a priority industry sector in the National Occupational Research Agenda to identify and provide intervention strategies for occupational health and safety issues.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] In the European Union, the European Agency for Safety and Health at Work has issued guidelines on implementing health and safety directives in agriculture, livestock farming, horticulture, and forestry.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] The Agricultural Safety and Health Council of America (ASHCA) also holds a yearly summit to discuss safety.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Extending over 4.8 billion ha in 2025 – the equivalent of one-third of the Earth's land surface – agriculture has a greater impact on land and water resources compared with any other economic sector.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Pressure on land, soil and water resources has seriously compromised the performance and future prospects of agriculture, resulting in further loss of productive land and reduced water availability for farming and other forms of agricultural production.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Agricultural expansion drives deforestation and is one of the primary causes of the degradation of carbon-rich ecosystems such as peatlands.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] An estimated 64% of agricultural land is at risk of pesticide pollution, which damages biodiversity by destroying pollinators, harms soil microbiota and makes agrifood systems less resilient to pests, pathogens and climate change.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Accounting for 72% of global freshwater withdrawals, a figure predicted to rise further in the future, agriculture contributes to and is increasingly affected by water scarcity.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Overexploitation of groundwater and seawater intrusion in coastal aquifers is widespread, with major implications for food security.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Overall production varies by country as listed.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Cropping systems vary among farms depending on the available resources and constraints; geography and climate of the farm; government policy; economic, social and political pressures; and the philosophy and culture of the farmer.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Shifting cultivation (or slash and burn) is a system in which forests are burnt, releasing nutrients to support cultivation of annual and then perennial crops for a period of several years.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Then the plot is left fallow to regrow forest, and the farmer moves to a new plot, returning after many more years (10–20).
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] This fallow period is shortened if population density grows, requiring the input of nutrients (fertilizer or manure) and some manual pest control.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Annual cultivation is the next phase of intensity in which there is no fallow period.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] This requires even greater nutrient and pest control inputs.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Further industrialization led to the use of monocultures, when one cultivar is planted on a large acreage.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Because of the low biodiversity, nutrient use is uniform and pests tend to build up, necessitating the greater use of pesticides and fertilizers.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Multiple cropping, in which several crops are grown sequentially in one year, and intercropping, when several crops are grown at the same time, are other kinds of annual cropping systems known as polycultures.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] In subtropical and arid environments, the timing and extent of agriculture may be limited by rainfall, either not allowing multiple annual crops in a year, or requiring irrigation.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] In all of these environments perennial crops are grown (coffee, chocolate) and systems are practiced such as agroforestry.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] In temperate environments, where ecosystems were predominantly grassland or prairie, highly productive annual farming is the dominant agricultural system.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Important categories of food crops include cereals, legumes, forage, fruits and vegetables.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Natural fibers include cotton, wool, hemp, silk and flax.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Specific crops are cultivated in distinct growing regions throughout the world.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Production is listed in millions of metric tons, based on FAO estimates.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Animal husbandry is the breeding and raising of animals for meat, milk, eggs, or wool, and for work and transport.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Working animals, including horses, mules, oxen, water buffalo, camels, llamas, alpacas, donkeys, and dogs, have for centuries been used to help cultivate fields, harvest crops, wrangle other animals, and transport farm products to buyers.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Livestock production systems can be defined based on feed source, as grassland-based, mixed, and landless.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] As of 2010, 30% of Earth's ice- and water-free area was used for producing livestock, with the sector employing approximately 1.3 billion people.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Between the 1960s and the 2000s, there was a significant increase in livestock production, both by numbers and by carcass weight, especially among beef, pigs and chickens, the latter of which had production increased by almost a factor of 10.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Non-meat animals, such as milk cows and egg-producing chickens, also showed significant production increases.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Global cattle, sheep and goat populations are expected to continue to increase sharply through 2050.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Aquaculture or fish farming, the production of fish for human consumption in confined operations, is one of the fastest growing sectors of food production, growing at an average of 9% a year between 1975 and 2007.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] During the second half of the 20th century, producers using selective breeding focused on creating livestock breeds and crossbreeds that increased production, while mostly disregarding the need to preserve genetic diversity.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] This trend has led to a significant decrease in genetic diversity and resources among livestock breeds, leading to a corresponding decrease in disease resistance and local adaptations previously found among traditional breeds.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Grassland based livestock production relies upon plant material such as shrubland, rangeland, and pastures for feeding ruminant animals.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Outside nutrient inputs may be used, however manure is returned directly to the grassland as a major nutrient source.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] This system is particularly important in areas where crop production is not feasible because of climate or soil, representing 30–40 million pastoralists.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Mixed production systems use grassland, fodder crops and grain feed crops as feed for ruminant and monogastric (one stomach; mainly chickens and pigs) livestock.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Manure is typically recycled in mixed systems as a fertilizer for crops.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Landless systems rely upon feed from outside the farm, representing the de-linking of crop and livestock production found more prevalently in Organization for Economic Co-operation and Development member countries.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Synthetic fertilizers are more heavily relied upon for crop production and manure use becomes a challenge as well as a source for pollution.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Industrialized countries use these operations to produce much of the global supplies of poultry and pork.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Scientists estimate that 75% of the growth in livestock production between 2003 and 2030 will be in confined animal feeding operations, sometimes called factory farming.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Much of this growth is happening in developing countries in Asia, with much smaller amounts of growth in Africa.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Some of the practices used in commercial livestock production, including the usage of growth hormones, are controversial.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Tillage is the practice of breaking up the soil with tools such as the plow or harrow to prepare for planting, for nutrient incorporation, or for pest control.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Tillage varies in intensity from conventional to no-till.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] It can improve productivity by warming the soil, incorporating fertilizer and controlling weeds, but also renders soil more prone to erosion, triggers the decomposition of organic matter releasing CO2, and reduces the abundance and diversity of soil organisms.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Pest control includes the management of weeds, insects, mites, and diseases.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Chemical (pesticides), biological (biocontrol), mechanical (tillage), and cultural practices are used.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Cultural practices include crop rotation, culling, cover crops, intercropping, composting, avoidance, and resistance.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Integrated pest management attempts to use all of these methods to keep pest populations below the number which would cause economic loss, and recommends pesticides as a last resort.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Nutrient management includes both the source of nutrient inputs for crop and livestock production, and the method of use of manure produced by livestock.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Nutrient inputs can be chemical inorganic fertilizers, manure, green manure, compost and minerals.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Crop nutrient use may also be managed using cultural techniques such as crop rotation or a fallow period.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Manure is used either by holding livestock where the feed crop is growing, such as in managed intensive rotational grazing, or by spreading either dry or liquid formulations of manure on cropland or pastures.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Water management is needed where rainfall is insufficient or variable, which occurs to some degree in most regions of the world.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Some farmers use irrigation to supplement rainfall.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] In other areas such as the Great Plains in the US and Canada, farmers use a fallow year to conserve soil moisture for the following year.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Recent technological innovations in precision agriculture allow for water status monitoring and automate water usage, leading to more efficient management.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Agriculture represents 70% of freshwater use worldwide.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] However, water withdrawal ratios for agriculture vary significantly by income level.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] In least developed countries and landlocked developing countries, water withdrawal ratios for agriculture are as high as 90 percent of total water withdrawals and about 60 percent in Small Island Developing States.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] According to 2014 report by the International Food Policy Research Institute, agricultural technologies will have the greatest impact on food production if adopted in combination with each other.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Payment for ecosystem services is a method of providing additional incentives to encourage farmers to conserve some aspects of the environment.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Measures might include paying for reforestation upstream of a city, to improve the supply of fresh water.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Different definitions exist for agricultural automation and for the variety of tools and technologies that are used to automate production.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] One view is that agricultural automation refers to autonomous navigation by robots without human intervention.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Alternatively, it is defined as the accomplishment of production tasks through mobile, autonomous, decision-making, mechatronic devices.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] However, FAO finds that these definitions do not capture all the aspects and forms of automation, such as robotic milking machines that are static, most motorized machinery that automates the performing of agricultural operations, and digital tools (e.g., sensors) that automate only diagnosis.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] FAO defines agricultural automation as the use of machinery and equipment in agricultural operations to improve their diagnosis, decision-making or performing, reducing the drudgery of agricultural work or improving the timeliness, and potentially the precision, of agricultural operations.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] The technological evolution in agriculture has involved a progressive move from manual tools to animal traction, to motorized mechanization, to digital equipment and finally, to robotics with artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Motorized mechanization using engine power automates the performance of agricultural operations such as ploughing and milking.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] With digital automation technologies, it also becomes possible to automate diagnosis and decision-making of agricultural operations.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] For example, autonomous crop robots can harvest and seed crops, while drones can gather information to help automate input application.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Precision agriculture often employs such automation technologies.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Motorized machines are increasingly complemented, or even superseded, by new digital equipment that automates diagnosis and decision-making.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] A conventional tractor, for example, can be converted into an automated vehicle allowing it to sow a field autonomously.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Motorized mechanization has increased significantly across the world in recent years, although reliable global data with broad country coverage exist only for tractors and only up to 2009.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Sub-Saharan Africa is the only region where the adoption of motorized mechanization has stalled over the past decades.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Automation technologies are increasingly used for managing livestock, though evidence on adoption is lacking.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Global automatic milking system sales have increased over recent years, but adoption is likely mostly in Northern Europe, and likely almost absent in low- and middle-income countries.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Automated feeding machines for both cows and poultry also exist, but data and evidence regarding their adoption trends and drivers is likewise scarce.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Measuring the overall employment impacts of agricultural automation is difficult because it requires large amounts of data tracking all the transformations and the associated reallocation of workers both upstream and downstream.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] While automation technologies reduce labor needs for the newly automated tasks, they also generate new labor demand for other tasks, such as equipment maintenance and operation.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Agricultural automation can also stimulate employment by allowing producers to expand production and by creating other agrifood systems jobs.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] This is especially true when it happens in context of rising scarcity of rural labor, as is the case in high-income countries and many middle-income countries.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] On the other hand, if forcedly promoted, for example through government subsidies in contexts of abundant rural labor, it can lead to labor displacement and falling or stagnant wages, particularly affecting poor and low-skilled workers.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Climate change and agriculture are interrelated on a global scale.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Global warming is already affecting agriculture, with effects unevenly distributed across the world.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] In a 2022 report, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change describes how human-induced warming has slowed growth of agricultural productivity over the past 50 years in mid and low latitudes.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Methane emissions have negatively impacted crop yields by increasing temperatures and surface ozone concentrations.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Warming is also negatively affecting crop and grassland quality and harvest stability.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Ocean warming has decreased sustainable yields of some wild fish populations while ocean acidification and warming have already affected farmed aquatic species.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Climate change will probably increase the risk of food insecurity for some vulnerable groups, such as the poor.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] In order to meet the demands of a growing global population, agriculture needs to produce about 50% more food, feed and fibre by 2050 compared with the volumes it generated in 2012, according to estimates by the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO).
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Achieving such objectives will place additional pressure on the world's already overstretched water, land and soil resources.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Crop alteration has been practiced by humankind for thousands of years, since the beginning of civilization.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Altering crops through breeding practices changes the genetic make-up of a plant to develop crops with more beneficial characteristics for humans, for example, larger fruits or seeds, drought-tolerance, or resistance to pests.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Significant advances in plant breeding ensued after the work of geneticist Gregor Mendel.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] His work on dominant and recessive alleles, although initially largely ignored for almost 50 years, gave plant breeders a better understanding of genetics and breeding techniques.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Crop breeding includes techniques such as plant selection with desirable traits, self-pollination and cross-pollination, and molecular techniques that genetically modify the organism.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Domestication of plants has, over the centuries increased yield, improved disease resistance and drought tolerance, eased harvest and improved the taste and nutritional value of crop plants.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Careful selection and breeding have had enormous effects on the characteristics of crop plants.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Plant selection and breeding in the 1920s and 1930s improved pasture (grasses and clover) in New Zealand.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Extensive X-ray and ultraviolet induced mutagenesis efforts (i.e. primitive genetic engineering) during the 1950s produced the modern commercial varieties of grains such as wheat, corn (maize) and barley.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] The Green Revolution popularized the use of conventional hybridization to sharply increase yield by creating "high-yielding varieties".
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] For example, average yields of corn (maize) in the US have increased from around 2.5 tons per hectare (t/ha) (40 bushels per acre) in 1900 to about 9.4 t/ha (150 bushels per acre) in 2001.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Similarly, worldwide average wheat yields have increased from less than 1 t/ha in 1900 to more than 2.5 t/ha in 1990.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] South American average wheat yields are around 2 t/ha, African under 1 t/ha, and Egypt and Arabia up to 3.5 to 4 t/ha with irrigation.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] In contrast, the average wheat yield in countries such as France is over 8 t/ha.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Variations in yields are due mainly to variation in climate, genetics, and the level of intensive farming techniques (use of fertilizers, chemical pest control, and growth control to avoid lodging).
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Investments into innovation for agriculture are long term.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] This is because it takes time for research to become commercialized and for technology to be adapted to meet multiple regions' needs, as well as meet national guidelines before being adopted and planted in a farmer's fields.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] For instance, it took at least 60 years from the introduction of hybrid corn technology before its adoption became widespread.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Agricultural innovation developed for the specific agroecological conditions of one region is not easily transferred and used in another region with different agroecological conditions.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Instead, the innovation would have to be adapted to the specific conditions of that other region and respect its biodiversity and environmental requirements and guidelines.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Some such adaptations can be seen through the steadily increasing number of plant varieties protected under the plant variety protection instrument administered by the International Union for the Protection of New Varieties of Plants (UPOV).
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Genetically modified organisms (GMO) are organisms whose genetic material has been altered by genetic engineering techniques generally known as recombinant DNA technology.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Genetic engineering has expanded the genes available to breeders to use in creating desired germlines for new crops.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Increased durability, nutritional content, insect and virus resistance and herbicide tolerance are a few of the attributes bred into crops through genetic engineering.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] For some, GMO crops cause food safety and food labeling concerns.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Numerous countries have placed restrictions on the production, import or use of GMO foods and crops.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] The Biosafety Protocol, an international treaty, regulates the trade of GMOs.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] There is ongoing discussion regarding the labeling of foods made from GMOs, and the EU has had GMO food labeling requirements since 1997.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] As of 2022, the United States requires food containing GMO ingredients to be labeled as well.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Herbicide-resistant seeds have a gene implanted into their genome that allows the plants to tolerate exposure to herbicides, including glyphosate.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] These seeds allow the farmer to grow a crop that can be sprayed with herbicides to control weeds without harming the resistant crop.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Herbicide-tolerant crops are used by farmers worldwide.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] With the increasing use of herbicide-tolerant crops, comes an increase in the use of glyphosate-based herbicide sprays.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] In some areas glyphosate resistant weeds have developed, causing farmers to switch to other herbicides.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Some studies also link widespread glyphosate usage to iron deficiencies in some crops, which is both a crop production and a nutritional quality concern, with potential economic and health implications.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Other GMO crops used by growers include insect-resistant crops, which have a gene from the soil bacterium *Bacillus thuringiensis* (Bt), which produces a toxin specific to insects.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] Some believe that similar or better pest-resistance traits can be acquired through traditional breeding practices, and resistance to various pests can be gained through hybridization or cross-pollination with wild species.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p01] In some cases, wild species are the primary source of resistance traits; some tomato cultivars that have gained resistance to at least 19 diseases did so through crossing with wild populations of tomatoes.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Agriculture is both a cause of environmental degradation and sensitive to environmental degradation, such as biodiversity loss, desertification, soil degradation and climate change, which cause decreases in crop yield.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Agriculture is one of the most important drivers of environmental pressures, particularly habitat change, climate change, water use and toxic emissions.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Agriculture is the main source of toxins released into the environment, including insecticides, especially those used on cotton.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] The 2011 UNEP Green Economy report stated that agricultural operations produced some 13 percent of anthropogenic global greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] This includes gases from the use of inorganic fertilizers, agro-chemical pesticides, and herbicides, as well as fossil fuel-energy inputs.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Agriculture imposes multiple external costs upon society through effects such as pesticide damage to nature (especially herbicides and insecticides), nutrient runoff, excessive water usage, and loss of natural environment.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] A 2000 assessment of agriculture in the UK determined total external costs for 1996 of £2,343 million, or £208 per hectare.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] A 2005 analysis of these costs in the US concluded that cropland imposes approximately $5 to $16 billion ($30 to $96 per hectare), while livestock production imposes $714 million.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Both studies, which focused solely on the fiscal impacts, concluded that more should be done to internalize external costs.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Neither included subsidies in their analysis, but they noted that subsidies also influence the cost of agriculture to society.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Agriculture seeks to increase yield and to reduce costs, often employing measures that cut biodiversity to very low levels.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Yield increases with inputs such as fertilizers and removal of pathogens, predators, and competitors (such as weeds).
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Costs decrease with increasing scale of farm units, such as making fields larger; this means removing hedges, ditches and other areas of habitat.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Pesticides kill insects, plants and fungi.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Effective yields fall with on-farm losses, which may be caused by poor production practices during harvesting, handling, and storage.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] The environmental effects of climate change show that research on pests and diseases that do not generally afflict areas is essential.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] In 2021, farmers discovered stem rust on wheat in the Champagne area of France, a disease that had previously only occurred in Morocco for 20 to 30 years.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Because of climate change, insects that used to die off over the winter are now alive and multiplying.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] A senior UN official, Henning Steinfeld, said that "Livestock are one of the most significant contributors to today's most serious environmental problems".
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Livestock production occupies 70% of all land used for agriculture, or 30% of the land surface of the planet.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] It is one of the largest sources of greenhouse gases, responsible for 18% of the world's greenhouse gas emissions as measured in CO2 equivalents.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] By comparison, all transportation emits 13.5% of the CO2.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] (This comparison later turned out to be an apples-and-oranges analogy.) It produces 65% of human-related nitrous oxide (which has 296 times the global warming potential of CO2) and 37% of all human-induced methane (which is 23 times as warming as CO2.) It also generates 64% of the ammonia emission.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Livestock expansion is cited as a key factor driving deforestation; in the Amazon basin 70% of previously forested area is now occupied by pastures and the remainder used for feed crops.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Through deforestation and land degradation, livestock is also driving reductions in biodiversity.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] A well documented phenomenon is woody plant encroachment, caused by overgrazing in rangelands.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Land transformation, the use of land to yield goods and services, is the most substantial way humans alter the Earth's ecosystems, and is the driving force causing biodiversity loss.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Estimates of the amount of land transformed by humans vary from 39 to 50%.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] It is estimated that 24% of land globally experiences land degradation, a long-term decline in ecosystem function and productivity, with cropland being disproportionately affected.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Land management is the driving factor behind degradation; 1.5 billion people rely upon the degrading land.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Degradation can be through deforestation, desertification, soil erosion, mineral depletion, acidification, or salinization.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] In 2021, the global agricultural land area was 4.79 billion hectares (ha), down 2 percent, or 0.09 billion ha compared with 2000.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Between 2000 and 2021, roughly two-thirds of agricultural land were used for permanent meadows and pastures (3.21 billion ha in 2021), which declined by 5 percent (0.17 billion ha).
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] One-third of the total agricultural land was cropland (1.58 billion ha in 2021), which increased by 6 percent (0.09 billion ha).
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Within the U.S., total agricultural land use is estimated to be 56%, and including grazing, animal agriculture constitutes around 80% of agricultural land.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Eutrophication, excessive nutrient enrichment in aquatic ecosystems resulting in algal blooms and anoxia, leads to fish kills, loss of biodiversity, and renders water unfit for drinking and other industrial uses.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Excessive fertilization and manure application to cropland, as well as high livestock stocking densities cause nutrient (mainly nitrogen and phosphorus) runoff and leaching from agricultural land.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] These nutrients are major nonpoint pollutants contributing to eutrophication of aquatic ecosystems and pollution of groundwater, with harmful effects on human populations.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Fertilizers also reduce terrestrial biodiversity by increasing competition for light, favoring those species that are able to benefit from the added nutrients.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Agriculture simultaneously is facing growing freshwater demand and precipitation anomalies (droughts, floods, and extreme rainfall and weather events) on rainfed areas fields and grazing lands.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Agriculture accounts for 70 percent of withdrawals of freshwater resources, and an estimated 41 percent of current global irrigation water use occurs at the expense of environmental flow requirements.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Within the U.S., agriculture accounts for about 80% of total water consumption, with animal agriculture making up half of agricultural consumption (around 40%).
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] It is long known that aquifers in areas as diverse as northern China, the Upper Ganges and the western US are being depleted, and new research extends these problems to aquifers in Iran, Mexico and Saudi Arabia.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Increasing pressure is being placed on water resources by industry and urban areas, meaning that water scarcity is increasing and agriculture is facing the challenge of producing more food for the world's growing population with reduced water resources.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] While industrial withdrawals have declined in the past few decades and municipal withdrawals have increased only marginally since 2010, agricultural withdrawals have continued to grow at an ever faster pace.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Agricultural water usage can also cause major environmental problems, including the destruction of natural wetlands, the spread of water-borne diseases, and land degradation through salinization and waterlogging, when irrigation is performed incorrectly.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Pesticide use has increased since 1950 to 2.5 million short tons annually worldwide, yet crop loss from pests has remained relatively constant.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] The World Health Organization estimated in 1992 that three million pesticide poisonings occur annually, causing 220,000 deaths.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Pesticides select for pesticide resistance in the pest population, leading to a condition termed the "pesticide treadmill" in which pest resistance warrants the development of a new pesticide.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] An alternative argument is that the way to "save the environment" and prevent famine is by using pesticides and intensive high yield farming, a view exemplified by a quote heading the Center for Global Food Issues website: 'Growing more per acre leaves more land for nature'.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] However, critics argue that a trade-off between the environment and a need for food is not inevitable, and that pesticides can replace good agronomic practices such as crop rotation.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] The Push–pull agricultural pest management technique involves intercropping, using plant aromas to repel pests from crops (push) and to lure them to a place from which they can then be removed (pull).
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Agriculture contributes towards climate change through greenhouse gas emissions and by the conversion of non-agricultural land such as forests into agricultural land.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] The agriculture, forestry and land use sector contribute between 13% and 21% of global greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Emissions of nitrous oxide, methane make up over half of total greenhouse gas emission from agriculture.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Animal husbandry is a major source of greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Approximately 57% of global GHG emissions from the production of food are from the production of animal-based food while plant-based foods contribute 29% and the remaining 14% is for other utilizations.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Farmland management and land-use change represented major shares of total emissions (38% and 29%, respectively), whereas rice and beef were the largest contributing plant- and animal-based commodities (12% and 25%, respectively).
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] South and Southeast Asia and South America were the largest emitters of production-based GHGs.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Climate change put significant part of crops in danger already at 1.5 degrees of warming.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] While in North America, Europe and central Asia the share of endangered crops is relatively little at this level of warming, in the Middle east and North Africa region for example, close to 50% of cropland is in danger.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] With further temperature rise the risk increase in all regions, in some more, in some less.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Globally the cropland area in safe climatic zone decrease for all the major crop groups as warming exceed 1.5 degrees.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Current farming methods have resulted in over-stretched water resources, high levels of erosion and reduced soil fertility.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] There is not enough water to continue farming using current practices; therefore how water, land, and ecosystem resources are used to boost crop yields must be reconsidered.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] A solution would be to give value to ecosystems, recognizing environmental and livelihood tradeoffs, and balancing the rights of a variety of users and interests.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Inequities that result when such measures are adopted would need to be addressed, such as the reallocation of water from poor to rich, the clearing of land to make way for more productive farmland, or the preservation of a wetland system that limits fishing rights.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Technological advancements help provide farmers with tools and resources to make farming more sustainable.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Technology permits innovations like conservation tillage, a farming process which helps prevent land loss to erosion, reduces water pollution, and enhances carbon sequestration.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Agricultural automation can help address some of the challenges associated with climate change and thus facilitate adaptation efforts.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] For example, the application of digital automation technologies (e.g. in precision agriculture) can improve resource-use efficiency in conditions which are increasingly constrained for agricultural producers.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Moreover, when applied to sensing and early warning, they can help address the uncertainty and unpredictability of weather conditions associated with accelerating climate change.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Other potential sustainable practices include conservation agriculture, agroforestry, improved grazing, avoided grassland conversion, and biochar.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Current mono-crop farming practices in the United States preclude widespread adoption of sustainable practices, such as 2–3 crop rotations that incorporate grass or hay with annual crops, unless negative emission goals such as soil carbon sequestration become policy.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] The food demand of Earth's projected population, with current climate change predictions, could be satisfied by improvement of agricultural methods, expansion of agricultural areas, and a sustainability-oriented consumer mindset.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Since the 1940s, agricultural productivity has increased dramatically, due largely to the increased use of energy-intensive mechanization, fertilizers and pesticides.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] The vast majority of this energy input comes from fossil fuel sources.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Between the 1960s and the 1980s, the Green Revolution transformed agriculture around the globe, with world grain production increasing significantly (between 70% and 390% for wheat and 60% to 150% for rice, depending on geographic area) as world population doubled.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Heavy reliance on petrochemicals has raised concerns that oil shortages could increase costs and reduce agricultural output.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Industrialized agriculture depends on fossil fuels in two fundamental ways: direct consumption on the farm and manufacture of inputs used on the farm.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Direct consumption includes the use of lubricants and fuels to operate farm vehicles and machinery.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Indirect consumption includes the manufacture of fertilizers, pesticides, and farm machinery.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] In particular, the production of nitrogen fertilizer can account for over half of agricultural energy usage.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Together, direct and indirect consumption by US farms accounts for about 2% of the nation's energy use.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Direct and indirect energy consumption by US farms peaked in 1979, and has since gradually declined.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Food systems encompass not just agriculture but off-farm processing, packaging, transporting, marketing, consumption, and disposal of food and food-related items.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Agriculture accounts for less than one-fifth of food system energy use in the US.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Plastic products are used extensively in agriculture, including to increase crop yields and improve the efficiency of water and agrichemical use.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] "Agriplastic" products include films to cover greenhouses and tunnels, mulch to cover soil (e.g. to suppress weeds, conserve water, increase soil temperature and aid fertilizer application), shade cloth, pesticide containers, seedling trays, protective mesh and irrigation tubing.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] The polymers most commonly used in these products are low-density polyethylene (LPDE), linear low-density polyethylene (LLDPE), polypropylene (PP) and polyvinyl chloride (PVC).
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] The total amount of plastics used in agriculture is difficult to quantify.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] A 2012 study reported that almost 6.5 million tonnes per year were consumed globally while a later study estimated that global demand in 2015 was between 7.3 million and 9 million tonnes.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Widespread use of plastic mulch and lack of systematic collection and management have led to the generation of large amounts of mulch residue.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Weathering and degradation eventually cause the mulch to fragment.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] These fragments and larger pieces of plastic accumulate in soil.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Mulch residue has been measured at levels of 50 to 260 kg per hectare in topsoil in areas where mulch use dates back more than 10 years, which confirms that mulching is a major source of both microplastic and macroplastic soil contamination.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Agricultural plastics, especially plastic films, are not easy to recycle because of high contamination levels (up to 40–50% by weight contamination by pesticides, fertilizers, soil and debris, moist vegetation, silage juice water, and UV stabilizers) and collection difficulties .
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Therefore, they are often buried or abandoned in fields and watercourses or burned.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] These disposal practices lead to soil degradation and can result in contamination of soils and leakage of microplastics into the marine environment as a result of precipitation run-off and tidal washing.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] In addition, additives in residual plastic film (such as UV and thermal stabilizers) may have deleterious effects on crop growth, soil structure, nutrient transport and salt levels.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] There is a risk that plastic mulch will deteriorate soil quality, deplete soil organic matter stocks, increase soil water repellence and emit greenhouse gases.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Microplastics released through fragmentation of agricultural plastics can absorb and concentrate contaminants capable of being passed up the trophic chain.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Agricultural economics is economics as it relates to the "production, distribution and consumption of [agricultural] goods and services".
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Combining agricultural production with general theories of marketing and business as a discipline of study began in the late 1800s, and grew significantly through the 20th century.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] In the United States, and elsewhere, food costs attributed to food processing, distribution, and agricultural marketing, sometimes referred to as the value chain, have risen while the costs attributed to farming have declined.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] This is related to the greater efficiency of farming, combined with the increased level of value addition (e.g. more highly processed products) provided by the supply chain.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Market concentration has increased in the sector as well, and although the total effect of the increased market concentration is likely increased efficiency, the changes redistribute economic surplus from producers (farmers) and consumers, and may have negative implications for rural communities.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] National government policies, such as taxation, subsidies, tariffs and others, can significantly change the economic marketplace for agricultural products.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Since at least the 1960s, a combination of trade restrictions, exchange rate policies and subsidies have affected farmers in both the developing and the developed world.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] In the 1980s, non-subsidized farmers in developing countries experienced adverse effects from national policies that created artificially low global prices for farm products.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Between the mid-1980s and the early 2000s, several international agreements limited agricultural tariffs, subsidies and other trade restrictions.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] However, as of 2009, there was still a significant amount of policy-driven distortion in global agricultural product prices.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] The three agricultural products with the most trade distortion were sugar, milk and rice, mainly due to taxation.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Among the oilseeds, sesame had the most taxation, but overall, feed grains and oilseeds had much lower levels of taxation than livestock products.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Since the 1980s, policy-driven distortions have decreases more among livestock products than crops during the worldwide reforms in agricultural policy.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Despite this progress, certain crops, such as cotton, still see subsidies in developed countries artificially deflating global prices, causing hardship in developing countries with non-subsidized farmers.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Unprocessed commodities such as corn, soybeans, and cattle are generally graded to indicate quality, affecting the price the producer receives.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Commodities are generally reported by production quantities, such as volume, number or weight.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Agricultural science is a broad multidisciplinary field of biology that encompasses the parts of exact, natural, economic and social sciences used in the practice and understanding of agriculture.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] The scientific study of agriculture began in the 18th century, when Johann Friedrich Mayer conducted experiments on the use of gypsum (hydrated calcium sulphate) as a fertilizer.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Research became more systematic when in 1843, John Lawes and Henry Gilbert began a set of long-term agronomy field experiments at Rothamsted Research Station in England; some of them, such as the Park Grass Experiment, are still running.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] In America, the Hatch Act of 1887 provided funding for what it was the first to call "agricultural science", driven by farmers' interest in fertilizers.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Agricultural policy is the set of government decisions and actions relating to domestic agriculture and imports of foreign agricultural products.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Governments usually implement agricultural policies with the goal of achieving a specific outcome in the domestic agricultural product markets.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Agricultural policy can also touch on food quality, ensuring that the food supply is of a consistent and known quality, food security, ensuring that the food supply meets the population's needs, and conservation.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Policy programs can range from financial programs, such as subsidies, to encouraging producers to enroll in voluntary quality assurance programs.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] A 2021 report finds that globally, support to agricultural producers accounts for almost US$540 billion a year.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] This amounts to 15 percent of total agricultural production value, and is heavily biased towards measures that are leading to inefficiency, as well as are unequally distributed and harmful for the environment and human health.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Crop use in animal agriculture accounts for one form of inefficiency.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Animal agriculture's estimated land use to produce one kilocalorie or gram of protein is 50 to 100 times that of plant-based alternatives.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Furthermore, the larger the livestock, the lower the energy efficiency (kilocalories obtained relative to kilocalories the animal consumes).
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] For instance, beef's energy efficiency is estimated to be 2%.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] There are many influences on the creation of agricultural policy, including consumers, agribusiness, trade lobbies and other groups.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Agribusiness interests hold a large amount of influence over policy making, in the form of lobbying and campaign contributions.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Political action groups, including those interested in environmental issues and labor unions, also provide influence, as do lobbying organizations representing individual agricultural commodities.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] The Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO) leads international efforts to defeat hunger and provides a forum for the negotiation of global agricultural regulations and agreements.
[src:alderney/agriculture-p02] Samuel Jutzi, director of FAO's animal production and health division, states that lobbying by large corporations has stopped reforms that would improve human health and the environment.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] British Forces Cyprus are stationed on this territory, including Ayios Nikolaos Station for signals intelligence.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Despite being under British control, Akrotiri and Dhekelia are integrated with the surrounding Cypriot communities and economies.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The areas are notable for their strategic geopolitical value and rich environmental features, including the Akrotiri Salt Lake, a protected wetland.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Education, policing, and healthcare services are provided in coordination with the Republic of Cyprus.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The SBAs also play a significant role in intelligence and communications operations across the Eastern Mediterranean.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Although not part of the European Union post-Brexit, the areas continue to be governed by protocols that align with certain EU laws to avoid disrupting the daily lives of residents.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Sovereign Base Areas were created in 1960 by the London and Zürich Agreements, when Cyprus achieved independence from the British Empire, as recorded by the United Nations in 1960 as treaty 5476.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The United Kingdom desired to retain sovereignty over these areas, as this guaranteed the use of UK military bases on Cyprus, including Royal Air Force (RAF) Akrotiri, and a garrison of the British Army.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The importance of the bases to the British is based on the strategic location of the island, at the eastern edge of the Mediterranean, close to the Suez Canal and the Middle East; the ability to use the RAF base as staging post for military aircraft; and for training.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] In July and August 1961, there were a series of bomb attacks against the pipeline carrying fresh water to the Dhekelia Sovereign Base Area.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The pipeline was breached by explosions twelve times.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] In the early 1970s, the United States built an over-the-horizon radar named Cobra Shoe, which could observe aeroplane operations and missile tests in southern Russia.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] This was operated by the RAF on behalf of the U.S.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] This augmented an earlier British system built in the early 1960s named Project Sandra.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The American use of the base was hidden from the Cypriot government due to sensitivities between governments.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] In 1974, following a military coup by the Cypriot National Guard, Turkey invaded the north of Cyprus, leading to the establishment of the internationally unrecognized Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] This did not affect the status of the bases.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Greek Cypriots fleeing from the Turkish forces were permitted to travel through the Dhekelia Sovereign Base Area and were given humanitarian aid, with those from Achna setting up a new village (Dasaki Achnas or Achna Forest) which is still in the Dhekelia Sovereign Base Area.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Turkish advance halted when it reached the edge of the Dhekelia Sovereign Base Area to avoid military conflict with the United Kingdom.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] In the Akrotiri Sovereign Base Area a tented refugee camp was set up at "Happy Valley", part of the Episkopi Cantonment, to house Turkish Cypriots fleeing from Limassol and the villages surrounding the Area.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] In 1975, they were flown out of RAF Akrotiri via Turkey to northern Cyprus.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Some Greek Cypriot refugees remain housed on land in the parts of Trachoni and Kolossi villages that fall within the Akrotiri Sovereign Base Area.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] As a result of the Turkish invasion, the British Government reinforced its military presence in the Sovereign Base Areas on Cyprus.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] While some reports suggest that prior to the invasion, the Government was looking to reduce Britain's presence on the island, following the invasion that proved to be strategically difficult.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Hence the British military presence remained on the island for the next fifty years.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] On 1 March 2026, as part of the 2026 Iran war, the base at Akrotiri was subject to a drone strike.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Ministry of Defence afterwards confirmed the drone was not launched from Iran.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] This preceded British Prime Minister Keir Starmer granting permission for U.S. forces to use the bases in the strikes.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] No casualties were reported and only minor damage was sustained on the base's runway.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] On 2 March, two further drones were intercepted by RAF forces near the island.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] British authorities decided to evacuate both the Akrotiri and Dhekelia bases as a result of the attacks, prompting the Cypriot government to instruct an evacuation of Akrotiri village itself.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Government announced that British forces on the island would be reinforced, with additional fighter aircraft and Wildcat helicopters (equipped with anti-drone-capable Martlet missiles), in order to better protect British installations from attack.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Royal Navy would deploy the air defence destroyer HMS Dragon to the region.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Following multiple offensive airstrikes by Iran on Cyprus during the 2026 Iran War, the Hellenic Navy deployed advanced FDI HN frigate Kimon and a MEKO-class frigate, Psara, to the Eastern Mediterranean.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The other area is Dhekelia Cantonment (Greek: Δεκέλεια pronounced [ðeˈceʎa]; Turkish: *Dikelya*), or the Eastern Sovereign Base Area (ESBA), which includes a base at Ayios Nikolaos plus parts of twelve village districts.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Joint Service Signal Unit (Cyprus) is located at Ayios Nikolaos Station, in the ESBA.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Ayios Nikolaus Station is an ELINT (electronic intelligence) listening installation of the UKUSA Agreement intelligence network.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The UKUSA signals intelligence system is sometimes known as "ECHELON".
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The sovereign bases were retained in 1960 to keep military bases in areas under British sovereignty, along with the rights retained to use other sites in what became the territory of the Republic.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] That makes them different from the other British Overseas Territories.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Cypriot government issues licences for antiquity excavation in the SBAs subject to British consent, and any movable antiquities found in excavations or otherwise discovered become Cypriot state property.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The territory is administered by an Administrator, who is also the Commander of British Forces Cyprus, which as of March 2026 is Major General Tom Bewick.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Administrator is officially appointed by the British monarch on the advice of the Ministry of Defence.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Administrator has all the executive and legislative authority of a governor of an overseas territory.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] A Chief Officer is appointed, and is responsible to the Administrator for the day-to-day running of the civil government, with subordinate Area Officers responsible for the civil administration of the two areas.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] British citizens are normally entitled to vote in United Kingdom elections, as British Forces or overseas electors.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The areas have their own legal system, distinct from the United Kingdom and the Republic of Cyprus.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] This consists of the laws of the Colony of Cyprus as of August 1960, amended as necessary.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The laws of Akrotiri and Dhekelia are closely aligned with, and in some cases identical to, the laws operating within the Republic of Cyprus.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Court of the Sovereign Base Areas is concerned with non-military offences committed by any person within Akrotiri and Dhekelia.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Law and order is maintained by the Sovereign Base Areas Police.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Offences involving British Forces Cyprus and military law are dealt with by the Cyprus Joint Police Unit.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Fire and rescue services are provided by the Defence Fire and Risk Management Organisation through stations at Episkopi, Akrotiri, Dhekelia and Ayios Nikolayos.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Defence Medical Services provide emergency ambulance cover based from medical centres in the main bases.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] All emergency services are accessible from any telephone using the Europe-wide emergency number 112.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Labour government, under whom the proposal appeared, was replaced by the Cameron–Clegg coalition whose defence review did not mention the issue.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Republic of Cyprus claims that the Sovereign Base Areas are a "remnant of colonialism".
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] On 30 June 2005 the House of Representatives of Cyprus unanimously adopted a resolution on the legal status of the base areas originally proposed by Vassos Lyssarides.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The UK government does not recognise Cypriot claims that the UK's sovereignty in the areas is limited.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] In July 2001, protests were held at the bases by local Cypriots, unhappy with British plans to construct radio masts at the bases as part of an upgrade of British military communication posts around the world.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Locals claimed the masts would endanger local lives and cause cancer, as well as have a negative effect on wildlife in the area.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Sovereign Base Areas Administration has carried out assessments and surveys into the effects on wildlife, which have fed into an "Akrotiri Peninsula Environmental Management Plan", published in September 2012.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] In 2004, the UK offered to cede 117 square kilometres (45 sq mi) of farmland as part of the rejected Annan Plan for Cyprus.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] In some Cypriot media it was stated that the proposed interdiction of the Syrian civil war, utilising Akrotiri and Dhekelia, could recklessly endanger the Cypriot populations near to those bases.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Two days earlier, on 27 August 2013, Cypriot foreign minister Ioannis Kasoulides had moved to calm Cypriot concerns, saying that the British bases were unlikely to play a major part in any intervention.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] A spike in the US Air Force arms delivery from US and NATO depots in Europe to Akrotiri was reported by the Israeli newspaper Haaretz, and "the illegal presence of thousands of American soldiers" at the base have drawn criticism.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] During his 2024 visit to the base dispatching surveillance planes to Gaza, the British prime minister Keir Starmer noted, "We can't necessarily tell the world what you're doing here" "for reasons that are obvious to you, the whole world is relying on you".
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Surveillance planes continued being dispatched towards Gaza after the ceasefire between Israel and Hamas began.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] In March 2026, during the 2026 Iran war, a drone strike was launched against the bases by Hezbollah.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Following the attack, the diplomatic tension raised higher between Britain and Cyprus, as domestic protests criticized the presence of the bases and being dragged into regional conflict.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] In April 2026, British Minister for the Armed Forces Al Carns, made it clear that there will be no negotiation about the bases, or ceding sovereignty over the bases.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] There is normally no passport check at the border from Akrotiri or Dhekelia to Cyprus.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Perhaps to help reduce any tensions in the area, outside of the bases much of the territory is indistinguishable from that controlled by Cyprus and casual visitors may not realize that they have crossed an international border.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The main road connecting all major cities on Cyprus's southern shore run non-stop through SBA: Some 7 km (5 miles) of the A6 highway through Akrotiri SBA and some 16 km (10 miles) of the A3 highway through Dhekelia SBA.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] More formal controls do exist at the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus boundary.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Possession of a passport or an EU-compliant national identity card is generally needed in Cyprus.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] A passport is required to travel between Cyprus/SBAs and Northern Cyprus.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Issues concerning the validity of car insurance and customs are specified by SBAs' administration.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Under Article 2(1) of the Protocol, the SBAs were partially part of the European Union Customs Union in three domains: VAT, agriculture and fisheries.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] However, the SBAs were already outside the EU.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Therefore, concerns were raised about the future status of about 15,000 Cypriots (EU citizens) working in the SBA following the UK's 2020 departure from the EU.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Cyprus, Ireland and Spain were the only three EU states that conducted bilateral talks with the UK on the Brexit issue.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The talks between the UK and the Republic of Cyprus started in October 2017.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Brexit withdrawal agreement has a protocol on the SBAs, with provisions essentially maintaining their previous status.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Akrotiri and Dhekelia cover 3% of the land area of Cyprus, a total of 254 km2 (98 sq mi) (split 123 km2 (47 sq mi) (48.5%) at Akrotiri and 131 km2 (51 sq mi) (51.5%) at Dhekelia).
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Akrotiri and Dhekelia have a border of 48 km (30 mi) and 108 km (67 mi) with Cyprus respectively.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Akrotiri also has a longer coastline than Dhekelia.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] 60% of the land is privately owned as freeholds by Cypriot citizens; the other 40% is controlled by the Ministry of Defence as Crown leasehold land.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] In January 2014, an agreement between the Cypriot and UK governments was signed, ensuring that residents and property owners in the British Bases will enjoy equal rights for the development of property.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] In addition to Akrotiri and Dhekelia, the Treaty of Establishment also provided for the continued use by the British Ministry of Defence and the British Armed Forces of certain facilities within the Republic of Cyprus, known as *Retained Sites*.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Akrotiri is located in the south of the island, near the city of Limassol (or Lemesos).
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Dhekelia is in the southeast, near Larnaca.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Both areas include military bases, as well as farmland and some residential land.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Akrotiri is surrounded by territory controlled by the Republic of Cyprus, but Dhekelia also borders on the United Nations (UN) buffer zone and the area controlled by the Turkish forces.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The villages of Xylotympou and Ormideia, also in the Republic of Cyprus, are enclaves surrounded by Dhekelia.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Dhekelia Power Station, divided by a British road into two parts, also belongs to the Republic of Cyprus.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The northern part is an enclave, like the two villages, whereas the southern part is located by the sea, and therefore not an enclave, though it has no territorial waters of its own.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Territorial waters of 3 nautical miles (5.6 km) are claimed, and the right according to the laws of the UN to extend the claim of up to 12 nautical miles (22.2 km) is reserved.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Cyprus is an important migration flyway for birds between Africa and Europe and millions of birds are killed yearly as they migrate over the island.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] To protect resident and migratory birds, BirdLife Cyprus and the RSPB survey areas of illegal trapping.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] More than 150 species of birds, over half of conservation concern, have been trapped in nets, or on limesticks, and it is estimated that organised crime gangs earn over 15 million euros yearly.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The dead birds are sold to provide the main ingredient for ambelopoulia — an illegal delicacy — in the Republic of Cyprus.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The 2015 survey estimated a maximum 19 km (12 mi) of mist nets across both the Republic and the British Territories, and more than 5,300 limesticks removed, mainly in the Republic.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] It is estimated that over 2 million birds were killed in 2015 including over 800,000 on British Territories.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Employing measures such as covert camera surveillance, including a drone, exclusion zones and impounding vehicles, trapping activity at Dhekelia fell by 77.5%.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] In 2016, an estimated 800,000 birds were killed at Dhekelia.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] In 2017, trapping activity fell by 77.5% and bird deaths to an estimated 180,000.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Episkopi Cliffs Important Bird Area lies mostly within the western base area, and covers much of the peninsula.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] It was identified as an IBA in 1989, and became recognised under the Ramsar Convention in 2003.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] 60% was designated as a Special Protection Area in 2010.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Over 300 bird species have been recorded in this area.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The wetlands, including the large salt lake, are an important habitat and bird hotspot.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] These wetlands are an important breeding spot for the ferruginous duck, which has nested there since 2005.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Other species that nest in the wetlands include the black-winged stilt, the Kentish plover, the spur-winged lapwing, and the stone-curlew.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Black francolins, Cyprus wheatears, Cyprus warblers, Eleonora's falcons, peregrine falcons, griffon vultures, European shags, European rollers, blue rock thrushs, and wallcreepers breed elsewhere in the area, especially around the cliffs.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The beaches in the British Sovereign Base Areas (SBAs) are important nesting sites for the endangered green *Chelonia mydas* and loggerhead *Caretta caretta* turtles.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The SBA Environment Department, assisted by a large volunteer effort, has monitored turtle nesting success on SBA beaches since 1990.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Disturbance to nesting turtles is an issue in some areas due to activities such as camping, driving on beaches and illegal fishing.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Sea turtles in Cyprus are protected as priority species under the Protection and Management of Nature and Wildlife Ordinance (implementing the provisions of the Habitats Directive), enacted in 2007.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] In December 2015, five Special Areas of Conservation (SACs) were designated in the Cyprus Sovereign Base Areas.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The five SACs designated are Akrotiri, Episkopi, Cape Pyla, Dhekelia and Agios Nikolaos.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The designations were made under the Protection and Management of Nature and Wildlife Ordinance and will support the existing network (NATURA 2000) of SACs in Cyprus and across Europe.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] When the areas were being established, the boundaries were deliberately drawn to avoid centres of population.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Approximately 18,195 people live in the areas.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] About 11,000 native Cypriots work in the areas, or on farmland within the boundaries of the areas.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The British military and their families make up the rest of the population.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Persons related to the territory may in theory be eligible to claim the British Overseas Territories citizenship (BOTC status) through a personal connection to the areas, i.e., birth on the territory before 1983, or born after 1983 to a parent who was born on the territory before 1983.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] In comparison, the 2002 Act bestowed British citizenship on all other BOTCs.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Hence, non-British and non-military personnel with a connection to the territory cannot live and work in the UK, and must use their Cypriot passports to apply for visas to the UK.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Under the terms of the 1960 agreement with Cyprus establishing the Sovereign Base Areas, the United Kingdom is committed not to use the areas for civilian purposes.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] This was stated in 2002 as the primary reason for the exclusion of the areas from the scope of the British Overseas Territories Act 2002.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] As of 2010, around 7,195 service personnel of British Forces Cyprus are based at Akrotiri and Dhekelia.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Service Children's Education oversees education for children of personnel and MoD employees.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Eastern Sovereign Base Area is served by Dhekelia Primary School and Ayios Nikolaos Primary School, which are feeders for King Richard School.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Western Sovereign Base Area is served by Episkopi Primary School and Akrotiri Primary School, which are feeders for St.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] No economic statistics are gathered for Akrotiri and Dhekelia.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The main economic activities are the provision of services to the military, as well as limited agriculture.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] When the territory under the effective control of the Republic of Cyprus switched currencies from the Cypriot pound to the euro in January 2008, Akrotiri and Dhekelia followed suit, making the Sovereign Base Areas the only territory under British sovereignty to officially use the euro.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Cypriot motorways pass through both areas, the most prominent case being the A3 motorway which runs for approximately 16km (10 miles) within the Dhekelia area.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] There is no public airport within the areas, but the RAF Akrotiri airbase is located there, which has a runway suitable for long-distance flights, but is not used for public flights.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The closest civilian international airport to the Akrotiri area is Paphos International Airport 40km (25 miles) away, while the closest to the Dhekelia area is Larnaka International Airport 15km (10 miles) away.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] As with the rest of Cyprus, there is no rail transport within the two areas.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Base Areas form part of the Republic of Cyprus telephone numbering plan, using the international prefix +357.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Landline numbers are in the same eight-digit format, with the last four digits being the line number.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Numbers in Dhekelia begin with the digits 2474.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Those in Akrotiri begin with the digits 2527.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The bases are issued different amateur radio call signs from the Republic of Cyprus.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Amateur radio stations on the bases use the International Telecommunication Union prefix of "ZC4", which is assigned to Great Britain.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] There are about 52 amateurs licensed in this manner.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Amateur radio direction finding identified RAF Akrotiri as the location of the powerful but now defunct shortwave numbers station "Lincolnshire Poacher".
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Several curtain antennas there have been identified as being used for these transmissions.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] BFBS Radio 1 and 2 are broadcast on FM and can be widely received across Cyprus.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] BFBS Television is now only available to viewers via satellite, having been confined to the SBAs or encrypted in 1997 for copyright reasons, before BFBS switched off its analogue transmitters in 2009.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The British East Mediterranean Relay Station was situated locally.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The most successful association football team in the territory is Ethnikos Achna FC in the Dhekelia region.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] They play in the Cypriot football league system and have played in the top tier Cypriot First Division for most of their existence.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] They represented Cyprus in the 2006–07 UEFA Cup, losing to RC Lens from France in Round 1.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Their stadium, Dasaki Stadium, hosted 6 matches in the 2024 UEFA European Under-17 Championship.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] Other teams in the territory also play in the Cypriot league system, for instance APEA Akrotiri.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] A separate league for British military teams, the Cyprus Forces Football League, is run by the Royal Air Force FA.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The Commander British Forces Cyprus Sporting Competition (CBF Cup), a multi-sport competition between teams representing bases and resident British infantry battalions, is held annually.
[src:alderney/akrotiri-and-dhekelia] The territory does not send delegations to the Commonwealth Games, and have not sent athletes to the Olympic Games through the British Olympic Association.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert was born in the Saxon duchy of Saxe-Coburg-Saalfeld to a family connected to many of Europe's ruling monarchs.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] At the age of 20, he married Victoria, his first cousin, with whom he had nine children.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Initially, he felt constrained by his role as consort, which did not afford him power or responsibilities.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] He gradually developed a reputation for supporting public causes, such as educational reform and the abolition of slavery worldwide, and was entrusted with running the Queen's household, office and estates.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] He was heavily involved with the organisation of the Great Exhibition of 1851, which was a resounding success.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Victoria came to depend more and more on Albert's support and guidance.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] He aided the development of Britain's constitutional monarchy by persuading his wife to be less partisan in her dealings with the British parliament, but he actively disagreed with the interventionist foreign policy pursued during Lord Palmerston's tenure as Foreign Secretary.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert died in 1861 at the age of 42, devastating Victoria so much that she entered into a deep state of mourning and wore black for the rest of her life.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] On the day of her death in 1901, their eldest son succeeded as Edward VII, the first British monarch of the House of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha, named after the ducal house to which Albert belonged.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert was born on 26 August 1819 at Schloss Rosenau, near Coburg, Germany, the second son of Ernest III, Duke of Saxe-Coburg-Saalfeld, and his first wife, Louise of Saxe-Gotha-Altenburg.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] His first cousin and future wife, Victoria, had been born earlier in the same year with the assistance of the same midwife, Charlotte von Siebold.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] He was baptised into the Lutheran Evangelical Church on 19 September in the Marble Hall at Schloss Rosenau, with water taken from the local river, the Itz.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] His godparents were his paternal grandmother, the Dowager Duchess of Saxe-Coburg-Saalfeld; his maternal grandfather, the Duke of Saxe-Gotha-Altenburg; the Emperor of Austria; the Duke of Teschen; and Emanuel, Count of Mensdorff-Pouilly.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] In 1825, Albert's great-uncle, Frederick IV, Duke of Saxe-Gotha-Altenburg, died, which led to a realignment of the Saxon duchies the following year; and Albert's father became the first reigning duke of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert and his elder brother, Ernest, spent their youth in close companionship, which was marred by their parents' turbulent marriage and eventual separation and divorce.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] After their mother was exiled from court in 1824, she married her lover, Alexander von Hanstein, Count of Pölzig and Beiersdorf.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] She presumably never saw her children again, and died of cancer at the age of 30 in 1831.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] The following year, their father married his niece Princess Marie of Württemberg; their marriage was not close, however, and Marie had little—if any—impact on her stepsons' lives.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] The brothers were educated privately at home by Christoph Florschütz and later studied in Brussels, where Adolphe Quetelet was one of their tutors.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Like many other German princes, Albert attended the University of Bonn, where he studied law, political economy, philosophy and the history of art.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] He played music and he excelled at sport, especially fencing and riding.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] His tutors at Bonn included the philosopher Fichte and the poet Schlegel.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] The idea of marriage between Albert and his first cousin Victoria was first documented in an 1821 letter from his paternal grandmother, the Dowager Duchess of Saxe-Coburg-Saalfeld, who said that he was "the pendant to the pretty cousin".
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] By 1836, this idea had also arisen in the mind of their ambitious uncle Leopold, who had been King of the Belgians since 1831.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] At this time, Victoria was the heir presumptive to the British throne.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Her father, Prince Edward, Duke of Kent and Strathearn, the fourth son of King George III, had died when she was an infant, and her elderly uncle, King William IV, had no surviving legitimate children.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Her mother, the Duchess of Kent, was the sister of both Albert's father—the Duke of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha—and King Leopold.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Leopold arranged for his sister, Victoria's mother, to invite the Duke of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha and his two sons to visit her in May 1836, with the purpose of meeting Victoria.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] William IV, however, disapproved of any match with the Coburgs, and instead favoured the suit of Prince Alexander, second son of the Prince of Orange.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Victoria was well aware of the various matrimonial plans and critically appraised a parade of eligible princes.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Victoria wrote to her uncle Leopold to thank him "for the prospect of *great* happiness you have contributed to give me, in the person of dear Albert ...
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] He possesses every quality that could be desired to render me perfectly happy." Although the parties did not undertake a formal engagement, both the family and their retainers widely assumed that the match would take place.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Victoria came to the throne on 20 June 1837, aged 18.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Her letters of the time show interest in Albert's education for the role he would have to play, although she resisted attempts to rush her into marriage.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] In the winter of 1838–1839, the prince visited Italy, accompanied by the Coburg family's confidential adviser, Baron Stockmar.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert returned to the United Kingdom with Ernest in October 1839 to visit Victoria, with the objective of settling the marriage.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert and Victoria felt mutual affection and the Queen proposed to him on 15 October 1839.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Victoria's intention to marry was declared formally to the Privy Council on 23 November, and the couple married on 10 February 1840 at the Chapel Royal, St James's Palace.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Just before the marriage, Albert was naturalised by an Act of Parliament, and granted the style of *Royal Highness* by an Order in Council.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Initially Albert was not popular with the British public; he was perceived to be from an impoverished and undistinguished minor state, barely larger than a small English county.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] The British prime minister, Lord Melbourne, advised the Queen against granting her husband the title of "King Consort"; Parliament also objected to Albert being created a peer—partly because of anti-German sentiment and a desire to exclude Albert from any political role.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert's religious views provided a small amount of controversy when the marriage was debated in Parliament: although as a member of the Lutheran Evangelical Church Albert was a Protestant, the non-Episcopal nature of his church was considered worrisome.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Of greater concern, however, was that some of Albert's family were Roman Catholic.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Melbourne led a minority government and the opposition took advantage of the marriage to weaken his position further.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] They opposed a British peerage for Albert and granted him a smaller annuity than previous consorts, £30,000 instead of the usual £50,000.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert referred to her as the "House Dragon", and manoeuvred to dislodge the Baroness from her position.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Within two months of the marriage, Victoria was pregnant.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert started to take on public roles; he became President of the Society for the Extinction of Slavery (slavery was still lawful in most parts of the world beyond the British Empire); and helped Victoria privately with her government paperwork.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] In June 1840, while on a public carriage ride, Albert and the pregnant Victoria were shot at by Edward Oxford, who was later judged insane.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Neither Albert nor Victoria was hurt, and Albert was praised in the newspapers for his courage and coolness during the attack.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] He was gaining public support as well as political influence, which showed itself practically when, in August, Parliament passed the Regency Act 1840 to designate him regent in the event of Victoria's death before their child reached the age of majority.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Their first child, Victoria, named after her mother, was born in November.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Eight other children would follow over the next seventeen years.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] All nine children survived to adulthood, which was remarkable for the era; biographer Hermione Hobhouse credited the healthy running of the nursery to Albert's "enlightened influence".
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] In early 1841, he successfully removed the nursery from Lehzen's pervasive control, and in September 1842, Lehzen left Britain permanently—much to Albert's relief.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] After the 1841 general election, Melbourne was replaced as prime minister by Sir Robert Peel, who appointed Albert chairman of the royal commission in charge of redecorating the new Palace of Westminster.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] The Palace had burned down seven years before, and was being rebuilt.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] The commission was set up to promote the fine arts in Britain as a patron and purchaser of pictures and sculpture.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] The commission's work was slow, and the palace's architect, Charles Barry, took many decisions out of the commissioners' hands by decorating rooms with ornate furnishings that were treated as part of the architecture.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert was more successful as a private patron and collector.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Among his notable acquisitions were early German and Italian paintings—such as Lucas Cranach the Elder's *Apollo and Diana* and Fra Angelico's *St Peter Martyr*—and contemporary pieces from Franz Xaver Winterhalter and Edwin Landseer.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Ludwig Gruner, of Dresden, assisted Albert in buying artworks of the highest quality.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert and Victoria were shot at again on both 29 and 30 May 1842, but were unhurt.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] The culprit, John Francis, was detained and condemned to death, although he was later reprieved.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Some of the couple's early unpopularity came about because of their stiffness and adherence to protocol in public, though in private the couple were more easy-going.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] In early 1844, Victoria and Albert were apart for the first time since their marriage when he returned to Coburg on the death of his father.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] By 1844, Albert had managed to modernise the royal finances and, through various economies, had sufficient capital to purchase Osborne House on the Isle of Wight as a private residence for their growing family.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Over the next few years a house modelled in the style of an Italianate villa was built to the designs of Albert and Thomas Cubitt.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert laid out the grounds, and improved the estate and farm.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] He managed and improved the other royal estates; his model farm at Windsor (Shaw Farm) was admired by his biographers, and under his stewardship the revenues of the Duchy of Cornwall—the hereditary property of the Prince of Wales—steadily increased.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Unlike many landowners who approved of child labour and opposed Peel's repeal of the Corn Laws, Albert supported moves to raise working ages and free up trade.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] In 1846, Albert was rebuked by Lord George Bentinck when he attended the debate on the Corn Laws in the House of Commons to give tacit support to Peel.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] During Peel's premiership, Albert's authority behind, or beside, the throne became more apparent.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] He had access to all the Queen's papers, was drafting her correspondence and was present when she met her ministers; he would even see them alone in her absence.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] In 1847, Victoria and Albert spent a rainy holiday in the west of Scotland at Loch Laggan, but heard from their doctor, Sir James Clark, that Clark's son had enjoyed dry, sunny days farther east at Balmoral Castle.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] The tenant of Balmoral, Sir Robert Gordon, died suddenly in early October, and Albert began negotiations to take over the lease from the owner, the Earl Fife.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] In May the following year, Albert leased Balmoral, which he had never visited.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] In September 1848 he, his wife and their older children went there for the first time.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] They came to relish the privacy it afforded.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] In 1847, Albert was elected Chancellor of the University of Cambridge after a close contest with the Earl of Powis.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert used his position as chancellor to campaign successfully for reformed and more modern university curricula by expanding the subjects taught beyond the traditional mathematics and classics to include modern history and the natural sciences.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Revolutions spread throughout Europe in 1848 as a result of a widespread economic crisis.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Throughout the year, Victoria and Albert complained about Foreign Secretary Palmerston's independent foreign policy, which they believed further destabilised Continental European powers.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert was concerned for many of his royal relatives, a number of whom were deposed by revolutionaries.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] He and Victoria, who gave birth to their daughter Louise during that year, spent some time away from London in the relative safety of Osborne.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Although there were sporadic demonstrations in England, no effective revolutionary action took place.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert gained public acclaim when he expressed paternalistic yet well-meaning and philanthropic views.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] In an 1848 speech to the Society for the Improvement of the Condition of the Labouring Classes, of which he was president, he expressed his "sympathy and interest for that class of our community who have most of the toil and fewest of the enjoyments of this world".
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] It was the "duty of those who, under the blessings of Divine Providence, enjoy station, wealth, and education" to assist those less fortunate than themselves.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] His progressive and relatively liberal ideas were expressed by his support of emancipation, technological progress, science education, the ideas of Charles Darwin, and the welfare of the working classes.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert led reforms in university education, welfare and the royal finances, and supported the campaign against slavery.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] He also had a special interest in applying science and art to manufacturing industry.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert sympathized with Jewish emancipation, and his influence was sought to secure the right of Jews to serve in parliament.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] In 1860, Albert used the opportunity of congratulating the Prince Regent of Prussia on the birth of their granddaughter Princess Charlotte of Prussia to raise concerns about various European matters, such as reform in the Austrian empire.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] In the letter, Albert proclaimed it "high time" that Emperor Franz Joseph I caused justice to be done to Protestants, Hungarians, and Jews, three groups that had long been faced wrongs under the Hapsburg monarchy in Austria.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] The Great Exhibition of 1851 arose from the annual exhibitions of the Society of Arts, of which Albert was president from 1843, and owed most of its success to his efforts to promote it.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert served as president of the Royal Commission for the Exhibition of 1851, and had to fight for every stage of the project.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] In the House of Lords, Lord Brougham fulminated against the proposal to hold the exhibition in Hyde Park.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Opponents of the exhibition prophesied that foreign rogues and revolutionists would overrun England, subvert the morals of the people, and destroy their faith.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert thought such talk absurd and quietly persevered, trusting always that British manufacturing would benefit from exposure to the best products of foreign countries.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Victoria opened the exhibition on 1 May 1851 in a specially designed and built glass building known as the Crystal Palace.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] A surplus of £180,000 was used to purchase land in South Kensington on which to establish educational and cultural institutions, including the Natural History Museum, Science Museum, Imperial College London and what would later be named the Royal Albert Hall and the Victoria and Albert Museum.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] The area was referred to as "Albertopolis" by sceptics.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] In 1852, John Camden Neild, an eccentric miser, left Victoria an unexpected legacy, which Albert used to obtain the freehold of Balmoral.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] As usual, he embarked on an extensive programme of improvements.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] The same year, he was appointed to several of the offices left vacant by the death of the Duke of Wellington, including the mastership of Trinity House and the colonelcy of the Grenadier Guards.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] With Wellington's death, Albert was able to propose and campaign for modernisation of the army, which was long overdue.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Thinking that the military was unready for war and that Christian rule was preferable to Islamic rule, Albert counselled a diplomatic solution to conflict between the Russian and Ottoman empires.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Palmerston was more bellicose, and favoured a policy that would prevent further Russian expansion.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Palmerston was manoeuvred out of the cabinet in December 1853, but at about the same time a Russian fleet attacked the Ottoman fleet at anchor at Sinop.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] The London press depicted the attack as a criminal massacre, and Palmerston's popularity surged as Albert's fell.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Within two weeks, Palmerston was re-appointed a minister.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] As public outrage at the Russian action continued, false rumours circulated that Albert had been arrested for treason and was being held prisoner in the Tower of London.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] By March 1854, Britain and Russia were embroiled in the Crimean War.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert devised a master plan for winning the war by laying siege to Sevastopol while starving Russia economically, which became the Allied strategy after the Tsar decided to fight a purely defensive war.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Early British optimism soon faded as the press reported that British troops were ill-equipped and mismanaged by aged generals using out-of-date tactics and strategy.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] The conflict dragged on as the Russians were as poorly prepared as their opponents.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] The Prime Minister, Lord Aberdeen, resigned, and Palmerston succeeded him.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] A negotiated settlement eventually put an end to the war by the March 1856 Treaty of Paris.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] During the war, Albert arranged the marriage of his fourteen-year-old daughter, Victoria, to Prince Frederick William of Prussia, but Albert delayed the marriage until Victoria was seventeen.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert hoped that his daughter and son-in-law would be a liberalising influence in the enlarging but very conservative Prussian state.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert promoted many public educational institutions.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Chiefly at meetings in connection with them, he spoke of the need for better schooling.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] A collection of his speeches was published in 1857.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Recognised as a supporter of education and technological progress, he was invited to speak at scientific meetings, such as the memorable address he delivered as president of the British Association for the Advancement of Science when it met at Aberdeen in 1859.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] His espousal of science met with clerical opposition; he and Palmerston unsuccessfully recommended a knighthood for Charles Darwin, after the publication of *On the Origin of Species*, which was opposed by the Bishop of Oxford.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert continued to devote himself to the education of his family and the management of the royal household.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] His children's governess, Lady Lyttelton, thought him unusually kind and patient, and described him joining in family games with enthusiasm.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] He felt keenly the departure of his eldest daughter for Prussia when she married her fiancé at the beginning of 1858, and was disappointed that his eldest son, the Prince of Wales, did not respond well to the intense educational programme that Albert had designed for him.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] At the age of seven, the Prince of Wales was expected to take six hours of instruction, including an hour of German and an hour of French every day.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] When the Prince of Wales failed at his lessons, Albert caned him.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Corporal punishment was common at the time, and was not thought unduly harsh.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Philip Magnus wrote in his biography of Albert's eldest son that Albert "tried to treat his children as equals; and they were able to penetrate his stiffness and reserve because they realised instinctively not only that he loved them but that he enjoyed and needed their company".
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert was a talented amateur musician and composer.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] For his wedding, he composed a duet, *Die Liebe hat uns nun vereint* ("Love has now united us").
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Felix Mendelssohn described Albert playing the Buckingham Palace organ "so charmingly and clearly and correctly that it would have done credit to any professional".
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] After tuition from George Elvey, the organist at St George's Chapel, Windsor, Albert composed several choral pieces for Anglican worship, including settings of the *Te Deum* and *Jubilate*, and an anthem, *Out of the Deep*.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] His secular compositions included a cantata, *L'Invocazione all'armonia*, and *Melody for the Violin*, which Yehudi Menuhin later described as "pleasant music without presumption".
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] In August 1859, Albert fell seriously ill with stomach cramps.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] His steadily worsening medical condition led to a sense of despair; the biographer Robert Rhodes James describes Albert as having lost "the will to live".
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert later had an accidental brush with death during a trip to Coburg in October 1860, when he was driving alone in a carriage drawn by four horses that suddenly bolted.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] As the horses continued to gallop toward a wagon waiting at a railway crossing, Albert jumped for his life from the carriage.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] One of the horses was killed in the collision, and Albert was badly shaken though his only physical injuries were cuts and bruises.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] He confided in his brother and eldest daughter that he sensed that his time had come.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Victoria's mother and Albert's aunt, the Duchess of Kent, died in March 1861, and Victoria was grief-stricken.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert took on most of the Queen's duties despite his continuing chronic stomach trouble.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] The last public event over which he presided was the opening of the Royal Horticultural Gardens on 5 June 1861.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] In August, Victoria and Albert visited the Curragh Camp, Ireland, where the Prince of Wales was attending army manoeuvres.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] At the Curragh, the Prince of Wales was introduced by his fellow officers to Nellie Clifden, an Irish actress.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] By November, Victoria and Albert had returned to Windsor, and the Prince of Wales had returned to Cambridge, where he was a student.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Two of Albert's young cousins, King Pedro V of Portugal and his brother Ferdinand, died of typhoid fever within five days of each other in early November.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] On top of that news, Albert was informed that gossip was spreading in gentlemen's clubs and the foreign press that the Prince of Wales was involved with Clifden.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert and Victoria were horrified by their son's indiscretion and feared blackmail, scandal or pregnancy.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Although Albert was ill and at a low ebb, he travelled to Cambridge to see the Prince of Wales on 25 November and discuss the indiscreet affair.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] In his final weeks, Albert suffered from pains in his back and legs.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Also in November 1861, the *Trent* Affair—the forcible removal of Confederate envoys from a British ship, the RMS *Trent*, by Union forces during the American Civil War—threatened war between the United States and Britain.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] The British government prepared an ultimatum and readied a military response.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert was gravely ill but intervened to defuse the crisis.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] In a few hours, he revised the British demands in a manner that allowed the Lincoln administration to surrender the Confederate commissioners who had been seized from the *Trent* and to issue a public apology to London without losing face.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] The key idea, based on a suggestion from *The Times*, was to give Washington the opportunity to deny that it had officially authorised the seizure and thereby to apologise for the captain's mistake.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] On 9 December, one of Albert's physicians, William Jenner, diagnosed him with typhoid fever.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert died at 10:50 pm on 14 December 1861 in the Blue Room at Windsor Castle, in the presence of the Queen and five of their nine children.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert's funeral was held on 23 December at St George's Chapel, Windsor Castle.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] His body was temporarily entombed in the chapel's Royal Vault.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] A year after his death, his remains were deposited at the Royal Mausoleum, Frogmore, which remained incomplete until 1871.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] The sarcophagus, in which both he and Victoria were eventually laid, was carved from the largest block of granite that had ever been quarried in Britain.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] The Queen's grief was overwhelming, and the tepid feelings that the public had for Albert were replaced by sympathy.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] The widowed Victoria never recovered from Albert's death; she entered into a deep state of mourning and wore black for the rest of her life.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert's rooms in all his houses were kept as they had been even with hot water brought in the morning and linen and towels changed daily.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Such practices were common in the houses of the very rich.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] After Albert's death, Victoria withdrew from public life and her seclusion eroded some of Albert's work in attempting to remodel the monarchy as a national institution by setting a moral, if not political, example.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert is credited with introducing the principle that the British royal family should remain above politics.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Before his marriage to Victoria, she supported the Whigs.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] For example, early in her reign, Victoria had managed to thwart the formation of a Tory government by Sir Robert Peel by refusing to accept substitutions that Peel wanted to make among her ladies-in-waiting.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Despite Albert's request for no effigies of him to be raised, many public monuments were erected all over the country and across the British Empire.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] The most notable are the Royal Albert Hall and the Albert Memorial in London.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] The plethora of memorials erected to Albert became so great that Charles Dickens told a friend that he sought an "inaccessible cave" to escape from them.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert showed a keen interest in the improvement of army training, and was involved in the establishment and development of Aldershot in Hampshire as a garrison town and training base in the 1850s.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] A wooden Royal Pavilion was built there in which he and Victoria would often stay when they attended military reviews.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert established and endowed the Prince Consort's Library at Aldershot, which still exists.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Biographies published after his death were typically heavy on eulogy.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Theodore Martin's five-volume *magnum opus* was authorised and supervised by Queen Victoria, and her influence shows in its pages.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Nevertheless, it is an accurate and exhaustive account.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Lytton Strachey's *Queen Victoria* (1921) was more critical, but it was discredited in part by mid-20th-century biographers such as Hector Bolitho and Roger Fulford, who, unlike Strachey, had access to Victoria's journal and letters.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Scholars dismiss popular myths about Albert, such as the claim that he introduced Christmas trees to Britain.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Recent biographers such as Stanley Weintraub portray Albert as a figure in a tragic romance who died too soon and was mourned by his lover for a lifetime.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] In the 2009 film *The Young Victoria*, Albert, played by Rupert Friend, is made into a heroic character.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] In the fictionalised depiction of the 1840 shooting, he is struck by a bullet, which did not happen in real life.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] In the United Kingdom, Albert was styled "His Serene Highness Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha" in the months before his marriage.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] He was granted the style of *Royal Highness* on 6 February 1840, and given the title of Prince Consort on 25 June 1857.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Upon his marriage to Queen Victoria in 1840, Prince Albert received a personal grant of arms, being the royal coat of arms of the United Kingdom differenced by a white three-point label with a red cross in the centre, quartered with his ancestral arms of Saxony.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] They are blazoned: "Quarterly, 1st and 4th, the Royal Arms, with overall a label of three points Argent charged on the centre with cross Gules; 2nd and 3rd, Barry of ten Or and Sable, a crown of rue in bend Vert".
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] The arms are unusual, being described by S.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Aveling as a "singular example of quartering differenced arms, [which] is not in accordance with the rules of Heraldry, and is in itself an heraldic contradiction." Prior to his marriage Albert used the arms of his father undifferenced, in accordance with German custom.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert's Garter stall plate displays his arms surmounted by a royal crown with six crests for the House of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha; these are from left to right: 1.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] "A bull's head caboshed Gules armed and ringed Argent, crowned Or, the rim chequy Gules and Argent" for Mark.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] "Out of a coronet Or, two buffalo horns Argent, attached to the outer edge of five branches fesswise each with three linden leaves Vert" for Thuringia.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] "Out of a coronet Or, a pyramidal chapeau charged with the arms of Saxony ensigned by a plume of peacock feathers Proper out of a coronet also Or" for Saxony.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] "A bearded man in profile couped below the shoulders clothed paly Argent and Gules, the pointed coronet similarly paly terminating in a plume of three peacock feathers" for Meissen.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] "A demi griffin displayed Or, winged Sable, collared and langued Gules" for Jülich.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] "Out of a coronet Or, a panache of peacock feathers Proper" for Berg.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] The supporters were the crowned lion of England and the unicorn of Scotland (as in the Royal Arms) charged on the shoulder with a label as in the arms.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert's personal motto is the German *Treu und Fest* (Loyal and Sure).
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] This motto was also used by Prince Albert's Own or the 11th Hussars.
[src:alderney/albert-prince-consort] Albert's many descendants include royalty and nobility throughout Europe.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] Alderney is unique amongst Channel Islands airports in having three operational runways.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] The main runway, 08/26 is 880 m (2,887 ft) long and is mainly asphalt.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] The two secondary runways are both grass, 13/31 being 733 m (2,405 ft) long, with 03/21 having a length of 497 m (1,631 ft).
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] The main runway is equipped with low-intensity lighting, with portable lighting being available on runway 13/31.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] The approach and runway lights were replaced in 2006.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] The terminal building, erected in 1968, contains an arrivals room and a departure lounge, with a check-in desk for the airport's only scheduled airline, Aurigny.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] Alderney is not a 24-hour airport; during winter, it is open Monday to Saturday from 0740 until 1830 and on Sunday from 0840 until 1830.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] During summer, it is open Monday to Thursday from 0740 until 1830 and Friday to Sunday from 0740 until 1920.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] The airport also has its own non-directional beacon, with runways 08 and 26 utilizing this for instrument approaches during Instrument meteorological conditions.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] Both runways also have an approved GPS (satellite) approach.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] This means that aircraft can land in lower visibility.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] Formal stands are not required due to the lack of space to accommodate nose-in-configured aircraft.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] For many years, the only direct scheduled links from the island were Southampton and Guernsey.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] Routes to other destinations such as Brighton, Bournemouth, Cherbourg, Exeter, Plymouth and Jersey were abandoned over the years due to what Blue Islands, for example, claimed was 'lack of interest'.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] These routes had been operated on and off by Aurigny and Blue Islands, but also Alderney Air Ferries, Air Sarnia, and Air Camelot during the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] The number of air routes to the island is at its lowest since the Second World War, except for a brief intermission during the 1967-8 period, when another airline (Glos Air, later to be Aurigny Air Services) was founded to fill the void (see below right).
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] From September 2013, airline Aurigny operated direct flights to Jersey on a trial basis for a period of six weeks.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] In April 2015, it was announced that the States of Alderney had asked airline Citywing to operate a seasonal Summer service between Alderney and Jersey using Let L-410 aircraft.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] However this service has not materialised.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] In January 2017, a new airline Air Alderney was set up with the intention of commencing direct flights using Britten-Norman Islander aircraft from Alderney to destinations including Jersey, Cherbourg, Lee-on–Solent, and Brighton.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] Despite considerable progress being made in acquiring aircraft and obtaining an Air Operator's Certificate, to date, operations have not yet commenced due to complications regarding ground operations at the intended destination airports.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] The States of Alderney set aside £400,000 from the £1 million allocated for a £12 million airport expansion proposed in 2019.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] This was to be used to pay for the redevelopment of the terminal, which is over 50 years old.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] During the 2020 COVID lockdown, while aircraft movements were low, airport staff refurbished the buildings, including repairs to a leaky flat roof on the 1960s terminal, and patched the runway.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] The runway was previously resurfaced in 1999 with a surface material having a design life of between 12 and 15 years.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] A major patch and repair was undertaken on the eastern end of the runway in the Autumn of 2016 to provide a short-term improvement, but by 2018, it was reported that major work would soon be required for continued safe operations.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] In 2020, the runway was patched and repaired during the covid lockdown by airport staff.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] On 4 July 2022, the States of Alderney backed plans to extend the runway from 2,877 ft (877m) to about 3,444 ft (1,050m) so that larger aircraft such as the ATR 72 plane can serve the island, giving an additional 20,000 seats per year to help tourism.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] The terminal building and fire station would also be improved as part of the scheme.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] Aurigny Air Services Ltd also stated that the expansion would reduce its operating costs by allowing it to retire the Dornier 228 from its fleet.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] In December 2022 the States of Guernsey agreed to spend £24m on extending, widening and strengthening the runway, construction of a new terminal building and refurbishment of the fire service facilities. £3.5 million will be contributed towards the costs by the States of Alderney.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] It was reported in January 2023 that land acquisition to allow the runway extension and repositioning of the track to the west had already started.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] It was also reported that tenders would be issued in the next few months, but work to secure Civil Aviation Authority and European Union Aviation Safety Agency approval for designs for the work would be needed, before issuing construction tenders.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] It was expected that Work would begin in 2024 and would be completed in the second quarter of 2025.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] However the project collapsed later in 2024 when the cheapest tender came in £13m over budget.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] In February 2026 it was reported that Deputies at the States of Guernsey voted in favour of spending £24 million to refurbish Alderney Airport runway with the aim of starting the work in 2027.
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] The repairs include resurfacing and realigning the main asphalt runway, which is set to be widened from 18 metres (59 ft) to 23 metres (75 ft), along with making taxiway improvements, but the runway length would remain the same at 870 metres (2,850 ft).
[src:alderney/alderney-airport] In June 2026 it was reported that the £24 million Runway Rehabilitation Project remained on track.
[src:alderney/alderney-bird-observatory] The observatory was featured on the BBC's Countryfile on 15 May 2016.
[src:alderney/alderney-bird-observatory] In its first year the observatory recorded 180 species including five new to the island, showing the importance of Alderney as a ″stop-over″ for migrant birds.
[src:alderney/alderney-bird-observatory] Thirteen thousand birds were ringed including 777 storm petrel (*Hydrobates pelagicus*) and 500 gannet (*Morus bassanus*).
[src:alderney/alderney-lighthouse] The Alderney Lighthouse was constructed from granite in 1912 under the guidance of local businessman William Baron.
[src:alderney/alderney-lighthouse] It was electrified in 1976, and automated in 1997, when the last resident lighthouse keeper left.
[src:alderney/alderney-lighthouse] The Trinity House Central Planning Unit in Essex controls and maintains the lighthouse.
[src:alderney/alderney-lighthouse] Before its construction there were several notable wrecks off Alderney, including the Leros.
[src:alderney/alderney-lighthouse] It still functions as a lighthouse, but is open for guided tours during the summer months when it is linked with the rest of the island by the Alderney Railway.
[src:alderney/alderney-lighthouse] In March 2011 the lighthouse was downgraded.
[src:alderney/alderney-lighthouse] The light reduced from 24hrs with a 23 nautical miles (43 km; 26 mi) range to dark hours only with a 12 nautical miles (22 km; 14 mi).
[src:alderney/alderney-lighthouse] This downgrade meant that the main beam was switched off, the lens shrouded and the light pulse now provided by a pair of LED lamps fixed to the sides of the tower.
[src:alderney/alderney-lighthouse] The fog signal was stopped at the same time.
[src:alderney/alderney] Alderney has an area of 3 square miles (8 km2), making it the third-largest island of the Channel Islands, and the second-largest in the bailiwick only to the island of Guernsey itself.
[src:alderney/alderney] Alderney is around 10 miles (16 km) to the west of the Cap de la Hague on the Cotentin Peninsula, Normandy, in France, 20 miles (32 km) to the northeast of Guernsey and 60 miles (100 km) from the south coast of Great Britain.
[src:alderney/alderney] It is the closest of the Channel Islands both to France and to the United Kingdom.
[src:alderney/alderney] It is separated from the Cap de la Hague by the dangerous Alderney Race (French: *Raz Blanchard*).
[src:alderney/alderney] As of March 2023, the island had a population of 2,167; natives are traditionally nicknamed *vaques* after the cows, or else *lapins* after the many rabbits seen in the island.
[src:alderney/alderney] Formally, they are known as *Ridunians*, from the Latin *Riduna*.
[src:alderney/alderney] The only parish of Alderney is the parish of St Anne, which covers the whole island.
[src:alderney/alderney] The main town, Saint Anne, historically known as *La Ville* ('The Town'), is often referred to as *St Anne's* by visitors and incomers, but rarely by locals (who, in normal conversation, still most frequently refer to the area centred on Victoria Street simply as *Town*).
[src:alderney/alderney] The town's "High Street", which formerly had a small handful of shops, is now almost entirely residential, forming a T-junction with Victoria Street at its highest point.
[src:alderney/alderney] The town area features an imposing church and an unevenly cobbled main street: Victoria Street (*Rue Grosnez*, the English name being adopted on the visit of Queen Victoria in 1854).
[src:alderney/alderney] There is one school (providing both primary and secondary education), a post office, hotels, restaurants, shops, and a bank.
[src:alderney/alderney] Other settlements include: Braye, Crabby, Longis, Mannez, La Banque, and Newtown.
[src:alderney/alderney] Alderney shares its prehistory with the other islands in the Bailiwick of Guernsey; it became an island in the Neolithic period as the waters of the English Channel rose.
[src:alderney/alderney] A cist survives near Fort Tourgis, and Longis Common has remains of an Iron Age site.
[src:alderney/alderney] The etymology of the island's name is obscure.
[src:alderney/alderney] It is known in Latin as *Riduna* but, as with the names of all the Channel Islands in the Roman period, there is a degree of confusion.
[src:alderney/alderney] *Riduna* may be the original name of Tatihou, while Alderney is conjectured to be identified with *Sarnia*.
[src:alderney/alderney] *Alderney*/*Aurigny* is variously supposed to be a Germanic or Celtic name.
[src:alderney/alderney] It may be a corruption of *Adreni* or *Alrene*, which is probably derived from an Old Norse word meaning "island near the coast".
[src:alderney/alderney] Alternatively, it may derive from three Norse elements: *alda* (swelling wave, roller), *renna* (strong current, race) and *öy* or *-ey* (island).
[src:alderney/alderney] Alderney may be mentioned in Paul the Deacon's *Historia Langobardorum* (I.6) as 'Evodia' in which he discussed a certain dangerous whirlpool.
[src:alderney/alderney] The name 'Evodia' may in turn originate from the seven 'Haemodae' of uncertain identification in Pliny the Elder's *Natural History* (IV 16 (30) or Pomponius Mela's *Chronographia* (III 6,54).
[src:alderney/alderney] Along with the other Channel Islands, Alderney was annexed by the Duchy of Normandy in 933.
[src:alderney/alderney] In 1042, William the Bastard, Duke of Normandy (later William the Conqueror, King of the English), granted Alderney to the Abbey of Mont Saint-Michel.
[src:alderney/alderney] In 1057, the Bishop of Coutances took back control of the island.
[src:alderney/alderney] After 1204, when mainland Normandy was incorporated into the Kingdom of France, Alderney remained loyal to the English monarch in his dignity of Duke of Normandy.
[src:alderney/alderney] Henry VIII of England undertook fortification works, but these ceased in 1554.
[src:alderney/alderney] Essex Castle perpetuates the name of the Earl of Essex, who purchased the governorship of Alderney in 1591.
[src:alderney/alderney] Prior to the Earl's execution for treason in 1601, he leased the island to William Chamberlain, and Alderney remained in the hands of the Chamberlain family until 1643.
[src:alderney/alderney] From 1612, a Judge was appointed to assist the Governor's administration of Alderney, along with the Jurats.
[src:alderney/alderney] The function of the Judge was similar to that of the Bailiffs of Guernsey and Jersey, and continued until 1949.
[src:alderney/alderney] During the Wars of the Three Kingdoms, Alderney was held by a Parliamentary garrison under Nicholas Ling, Lieutenant-Governor.
[src:alderney/alderney] Ling built Government House (now the Island Hall).
[src:alderney/alderney] The de Carterets of Jersey acquired the governorship, later passing it to Sir Edmund Andros of Guernsey, from whom the Guernsey family of Le Mesurier inherited it, thus establishing a hereditary line of governors that lasted until 1825.
[src:alderney/alderney] Henry Le Mesurier prospered through privateering, and moved the harbour from Longis to Braye, building a jetty there in 1736.
[src:alderney/alderney] Warehouses and dwellings were built at Braye, and the export of cattle generated wealth for the economy.
[src:alderney/alderney] The Court House was built in 1770 and a school in 1790.
[src:alderney/alderney] A Methodist chapel was constructed in 1790, following John Wesley's visit in 1787.
[src:alderney/alderney] An optical telegraph tower was constructed above La Foulère in 1811, enabling signals to be relayed visually to Le Mât in Sark and on to Guernsey – early warning of attack during the Napoleonic Wars was of strategic importance.
[src:alderney/alderney] With the end of those wars privateering was ended and smuggling suppressed, leading to economic difficulties.
[src:alderney/alderney] The last of the hereditary Governors, John Le Mesurier, resigned his patent to the Crown in 1825, and since then authority has been exercised by the States of Alderney, as amended by the constitutional settlement of 1948.
[src:alderney/alderney] The British Government decided to undertake massive fortifications in the 19th century and to create a strategic harbour to deter attacks from France.
[src:alderney/alderney] The harbour was never completed – the remaining breakwater (designed by James Walker) is one of the island's landmarks, and is longer than any breakwater in the UK.
[src:alderney/alderney] Queen Victoria and Prince Albert visited Alderney on 9 August 1854.
[src:alderney/alderney] The Albert Memorial and the renaming of Rue Grosnez to Victoria Street commemorate this visit.
[src:alderney/alderney] At the same time as the breakwater was being built in the 1850s, the island was fortified by a string of 13 forts, designed to protect the harbour of refuge.
[src:alderney/alderney] The accommodation quarters of several of the forts have been converted into apartments; two are now private homes; and one, Fort Clonque, at the end of a causeway that can be flooded at high tide, belongs to the Landmark Trust and can be rented for holidays.
[src:alderney/alderney] Scenes from the film *Seagulls Over Sorrento* were shot at Fort Clonque in 1953.
[src:alderney/alderney] Some of the forts are now in varying stages of dereliction, the most ruined being Les Hommeaux Florains, perched on outlying rocks, its access causeway and bridge having been swept away long ago.
[src:alderney/alderney] Houmet Herbé resembles a Crusader castle with its squat round towers.
[src:alderney/alderney] Like many of the forts, it included such apparently anachronistic features as a drawbridge and machicolation, which were still common in military architecture of the period.
[src:alderney/alderney] In June 1940, almost the entire population of Alderney of 1,400 was evacuated to Britain.
[src:alderney/alderney] Most went on the official evacuation boats sent from mainland Britain.
[src:alderney/alderney] Some, however, decided to make their own way, mostly via Guernsey, but due to the impending occupation many found themselves unable to leave and were forced to stay on Guernsey for the duration of the war.
[src:alderney/alderney] Eighteen Alderney people elected not to leave with the general evacuation.
[src:alderney/alderney] However, boats from Guernsey came and collected some of them before the German Army arrived, on the basis that it was best for their personal safety.
[src:alderney/alderney] During the Second World War, the Channel Islands were the only part of the British Isles that was occupied by Germany, although other parts of the Empire were occupied by the Axis powers.
[src:alderney/alderney] The Germans arrived to a nearly deserted island, and began to follow their orders to fortify Alderney as part of Hitler's Atlantic Wall.
[src:alderney/alderney] In January 1942, they built four camps in Alderney: two work camps, Lager Helgoland and Lager Borkum, and two concentration camps, Lager Sylt and Lager Norderney.
[src:alderney/alderney] The jail behind the main police station was used by the Nazis as a prison.
[src:alderney/alderney] The camps were built by the Nazi Organisation Todt (OT) to house the labour used to build fortifications including bunkers, gun emplacements, tunnels, air-raid shelters and other concrete and field fortifications.
[src:alderney/alderney] Lager Norderney, containing Russian and Polish POWs, and the Lager Sylt camp holding Jewish slave labourers, were transferred to SS administration in March 1943 under the control of *Hauptsturmführer* Maximilian List.
[src:alderney/alderney] There are 397 graves in Alderney, which when added to the men who died in ships, takes the total to over 700 out of a total inmate population of 6,000 who died before the camps were closed and the remaining inmates transferred to France in 1944.
[src:alderney/alderney] Evidence, however, was all over the island, with concrete fortifications and graveyards for the prisoners kept there during the occupation.
[src:alderney/alderney] The Royal Navy blockaded the islands from time to time, particularly following the liberation of Normandy in 1944.
[src:alderney/alderney] Intense negotiations resulted in some Red Cross humanitarian aid, but there was considerable hunger and privation during the five years of German occupation, particularly in the final months when the Germans themselves were close to starvation.
[src:alderney/alderney] The Germans surrendered Alderney on 16 May 1945, eight days after the Allies formally accepted the unconditional surrender of the armed forces of Nazi Germany and the end of World War II in Europe, and seven days after the liberation of Guernsey and Jersey.
[src:alderney/alderney] 2,332 German prisoners of war were removed from Alderney on 20 May 1945, leaving 500 Germans to undertake clearing up operations under British military supervision.
[src:alderney/alderney] The people of Alderney could not start returning until December 1945 due to the huge cleanup operation needed simply to make the island safe for civilians.
[src:alderney/alderney] When the islanders returned home they were shocked to see the state of the island, with many houses completely derelict: the Germans had burned anything wooden, including front doors, for fuel.
[src:alderney/alderney] Archival and object evidence of the general evacuation in 1940 and the subsequent occupation of Alderney can be found in the Alderney Society Museum.
[src:alderney/alderney] In 1949, two former SS officials from the Lager Norderney concentration camp, SS Obersturmführer Adam Adler and Lagerführer Heinrich Evers, were prosecuted in France for crimes committed during their administration of the camp.
[src:alderney/alderney] Adler was sentenced to ten years, while Evers received a seven-year sentence.
[src:alderney/alderney] Members of the Association des Anciens Déportés d'Aurigny considered the sentences overly lenient.
[src:alderney/alderney] A 1945 British military report, known as the Pantcheff Report, documented that eight French nationals had perished in the Alderney camps.
[src:alderney/alderney] In May 2024, an investigative commission led by Lord Pickles concluded that between 641 and 1,027 individuals likely died in the Nazi camps on Alderney.
[src:alderney/alderney] The report highlighted the atrocious conditions faced by forced labourers, who endured starvation, dangerously long hours, hazardous construction tasks, frequent abuse, torture, inadequate housing, and, in some cases, execution.
[src:alderney/alderney] A series of tunnels also remain in place on Alderney, constructed by forced labour.
[src:alderney/alderney] These are in varying degrees of decay, being left open to the public and the elements.
[src:alderney/alderney] For two years after the end of the war, Alderney was operated as a communal farm.
[src:alderney/alderney] Craftsmen were paid by their employers, while others were paid by the local government out of the profit from the sales of farm produce.
[src:alderney/alderney] Remaining profits were put aside to repay the British Government for repairing and rebuilding the island.
[src:alderney/alderney] The local people resented being unable to control their own land; this led to the United Kingdom Home Office setting up an enquiry that led to the "Government of Alderney Law 1948", which came into force on 1 January 1949.
[src:alderney/alderney] The law organised the construction and election of the States of Alderney and the justice system; and, for the first time in Alderney, the imposition of taxes.
[src:alderney/alderney] The legislature and judiciary were separated.
[src:alderney/alderney] The position of Judge, who had headed the island's government since the resignation of the last Governor in 1825, was abolished, and the Jurats were removed from their legislative function.
[src:alderney/alderney] Because of the island's small population, it was believed that the island could not be self-sufficient in running the airport and the harbour, or providing services that would match those of the UK.
[src:alderney/alderney] Taxes were therefore collected into the general Bailiwick of Guernsey revenue funds at the same rate as in Guernsey, and administered by the States of Guernsey.
[src:alderney/alderney] Guernsey became responsible for providing many government functions and services.
[src:alderney/alderney] The 20th century saw much change in Alderney, from the building of the airport in the late 1930s to the death of the last speakers of the island's Auregnais language, a dialect of the Norman language.
[src:alderney/alderney] The economy has gone from depending largely on agriculture to earning money from the tourism and finance industries.
[src:alderney/alderney] E-commerce has become increasingly important, and the island hosts the domain name registry for both Bailiwicks and dozens of gambling website operators.
[src:alderney/alderney] Alderney has a full regulatory authority in operation.
[src:alderney/alderney] The States of Alderney (French: États d'Aurigny) is the legislature of the island; it sends two representatives to the States of Guernsey as well.
[src:alderney/alderney] The origin of the States is unknown, but it has operated from the Middle Ages.
[src:alderney/alderney] The States of Alderney consists of the President, directly elected every four years, and ten States Members, half elected every two years for a four-year mandate.
[src:alderney/alderney] The whole island is a single constituency.
[src:alderney/alderney] William Tate was elected president in June 2019.
[src:alderney/alderney] These are known as 'the transferred services'.
[src:alderney/alderney] Transferred services include policing, customs and excise, airport operations, health, education, social services, childcare and adoption.
[src:alderney/alderney] (The States of Alderney retains policy control of aviation to and from the island).
[src:alderney/alderney] In return for providing the transferred services Guernsey levies various taxes and duties on Alderney.
[src:alderney/alderney] Immigration is the responsibility of the UK (UK law applies), with day-to-day operations carried out by the Guernsey Border Agency.
[src:alderney/alderney] In addition to the transferred services, both the UK and Guernsey may legislate on other matters with the consent of the States of Alderney.
[src:alderney/alderney] The Court of Alderney exercises unlimited original jurisdiction in civil matters and limited jurisdiction in criminal matters.
[src:alderney/alderney] The Court sits with a Chairman (the Judge of Alderney) and at least three of the six Jurats.
[src:alderney/alderney] Appeals are made to the Royal Court of Guernsey, which also exercises some original jurisdiction in criminal matters in Alderney, and thence to the Judicial Committee of the Privy Council.
[src:alderney/alderney] For a number of taxation purposes, Alderney is treated as if it were part of Guernsey.
[src:alderney/alderney] Income Tax is administered by the Guernsey Revenue Service but there are some differences between Alderney and Guernsey Income Tax, specifically in the matter of the cap on Income Tax (which is set lower in Alderney than in Guernsey).
[src:alderney/alderney] From 2016, Alderney took back control of Tax on Real Property (TRP).
[src:alderney/alderney] From 2021, Alderney is responsible for setting the rate and collecting the Taxation on Real Property (TRP), with Occupier's Rates (OR) now included within that bill.
[src:alderney/alderney] Alderney now also receives Motor Fuel Excise Duty and Document Duty on property conveyances.
[src:alderney/alderney] The climate of Alderney is temperate, moderated by the sea, and summers are usually warmer than elsewhere in the British Isles.
[src:alderney/alderney] Under the Köppen climate classification, Alderney has an oceanic climate (Cfb), similar to a warm-summer Mediterranean climate (Csb).
[src:alderney/alderney] Alderney has cool, wet winters and mild summers with moderate rainfall.
[src:alderney/alderney] February is the coldest month with an average high of 8 °C (47 °F), and a low of 4 °C (40 °F).
[src:alderney/alderney] July and August are the warmest months, with an average high of 19 °C (66 °F), and a low of 13 to 14 °C (around 56 °F).
[src:alderney/alderney] October is the wettest month with 107.2 mm (4.22 in) of rain, and April is the driest month with 42.4 mm (1.67 in).
[src:alderney/alderney] Average annual sunshine hours are around 1780.
[src:alderney/alderney] Alderney is similar to the other Channel Islands in having sheer cliffs broken by stretches of sandy beach and dunes.
[src:alderney/alderney] The highest point is on the central plateau of the island at 296 feet (90 metres).
[src:alderney/alderney] Alderney and its surrounding islets support a rich flora and fauna.
[src:alderney/alderney] Trees are rather scarce, as many were cut down in the 17th century to fuel the lighthouses on Alderney and the Casquets.
[src:alderney/alderney] Those trees that remain include cabbage trees (due to the mild climate – often miscalled "palms" but of the asparagus family), and there are some small woods dotted about the island.
[src:alderney/alderney] Puffins on Burhou and gannet on Les Étacs (popularly called Gannet Rock) just off Alderney are a favourite of many visitors to the island.
[src:alderney/alderney] About a quarter of Alderney hedgehogs are of the "white" or "blonde" variety, which does not carry fleas.
[src:alderney/alderney] These are not albinos, but descent of rarely met blonde European hedgehogs, with a blonde pair released on the island in the 1960s.
[src:alderney/alderney] The island had its own breed of cattle, called the Alderney.
[src:alderney/alderney] The pure breed became extinct in 1944, but hybrids remain elsewhere, though no longer on Alderney.
[src:alderney/alderney] In August 2005, the west coast of Alderney and associated islands, including Burhou and Ortac, were designated as Ramsar wetlands of international importance.
[src:alderney/alderney] The Alderney Wildlife Trust helps to manage the two nature reserves, at Longis and Vau du Saou.
[src:alderney/alderney] The island is surrounded by rocks, which have caused hundreds of wrecks.
[src:alderney/alderney] There are treacherous tidal streams on either side of the island: the Swinge between Alderney and Burhou, just outside the harbour, and Le Raz between the island and the Normandy mainland.
[src:alderney/alderney] The geology of Alderney is mostly granites from the Precambrian period.
[src:alderney/alderney] The language of the island is now English with a few minor variants, comprising a form of Channel Island English.
[src:alderney/alderney] For centuries the island had its own dialect of the Norman language called Auregnais, now extinct.
[src:alderney/alderney] It was primarily a spoken language, with only a few known poems and written works using it.
[src:alderney/alderney] French was once widely used on the island, and increasingly replaced Auregnais from the late 19th century onward, but it ceased to be an official language there in 1966.
[src:alderney/alderney] However, there is a strong cultural legacy of both languages in the island: most of the local place-names are in French or Auregnais, as are many local surnames.
[src:alderney/alderney] The pronunciation of various local names is also dialectal, e.g.
[src:alderney/alderney] Dupont as "dip-oh" rather than in the traditional Parisian fashion, and Saye (the name of a beach on the island) as "soy".
[src:alderney/alderney] One or two French/Auregnais words are still in common use, e.g.
[src:alderney/alderney] *vraic* (seaweed fertiliser), as well as *impôt,* which is the word used for the island's landfill.
[src:alderney/alderney] Island sports include golf, fishing and water sports, supported by clubs and associations.
[src:alderney/alderney] Alderney competes in the biennial Island Games.
[src:alderney/alderney] Athletes from Alderney have also competed at the Commonwealth Games as part of the Guernsey team.
[src:alderney/alderney] Every September, the Alderney Air Races attract a number of aircraft to compete in the deciding and final round for the European Air Racing championship, organised by the Royal Aero Club.
[src:alderney/alderney] This involves high-speed circuits round the airfield, lighthouse, Casquets and then back around.
[src:alderney/alderney] The Alderney football team plays in the annual Muratti Vase alongside teams from fellow Channel Islands, Guernsey and Jersey.
[src:alderney/alderney] Since the competition started in 1905, Alderney's sole championship victory was in 1920.
[src:alderney/alderney] Partly because of the tourist industry, but mainly to the Ridunians' own drinking culture (there is a common expression elsewhere in the Channel Islands that Alderney is composed of 'two thousand alcoholics, clinging to a rock'), there are many restaurants and public houses.
[src:alderney/alderney] The States of Alderney passed pub anti-smoking legislation recently in comparison to the rest of the British Isles.
[src:alderney/alderney] Following the President's casting vote on 13 January 2010, the legislation came into force at 4 am on 1 June 2010 with Guernsey, Jersey, the UK, and the Isle of Man all having outlawed this at a previous stage.
[src:alderney/alderney] Notable residents of Alderney include authors T.
[src:alderney/alderney] White (*The Once and Future King*) and Elisabeth Beresford (The Wombles), cricket commentator John Arlott, cricketer Sir Ian Botham, Beatles producer Sir George Martin, actress Dame Julie Andrews, and Olympic swimmer Duncan Goodhew.
[src:alderney/alderney] Local TV coverage is provided by BBC Channel Islands and ITV Channel Television.
[src:alderney/alderney] Television signals are received from the island's relay transmitter situated in the eastern part of Alderney.
[src:alderney/alderney] The island is also served by both BBC Radio Guernsey on 99 FM and Island FM on 93.7 FM which both broadcast from St.
[src:alderney/alderney] Alderney has its own radio station, QUAY-FM, which broadcasts on 107.1 and online.
[src:alderney/alderney] Initially it only operated at seasonal highpoints such as the summer Alderney Week festival, but from 2015 it has broadcast 24 hours a day.
[src:alderney/alderney] Alderney Week is the island's annual summer festival, beginning the first Monday of August and lasting six days, it involves islanders and attracts visitors.
[src:alderney/alderney] Miss Alderney is chosen during the Easter Holiday weekend each year at a public event held at the Island Hall.
[src:alderney/alderney] Comedy Rocks is an annual run of live stand up comedy gigs mid to late July and early August.
[src:alderney/alderney] The shows feature well known and established comedians from the UK comedy circuit, and have so far featured BBC Radio 4's Marcus Brigstocke, Zoe Lyons and *I'm a Celebrity...Get Me Out of Here!* runner-up Joel Dommett.
[src:alderney/alderney] Every year in mid-September Alderney hosts a motorsport weekend that is organized by the Guernsey Kart and Motor Club.
[src:alderney/alderney] The event has been held for more than 20 years.
[src:alderney/alderney] The event attracts Guernsey drivers who come to Alderney with high powered cars, motorbikes, sidecars and karts.
[src:alderney/alderney] Race vehicles are shipped to Alderney two days before the event.
[src:alderney/alderney] On the Friday, a sprint is held on the public roads of Fort Corbelets in the east of the island which are closed for the event.
[src:alderney/alderney] The following day a hill climb is held at Fort Tourgis in the west of the island and on a public road which is closed for the event.
[src:alderney/alderney] Local Alderney people watch as the closed roads have vehicles racing at high speed where normally speed limits of 35 miles per hour (56 kilometres per hour) apply.
[src:alderney/alderney] The annual Alderney Performing Arts Festival began in 2013, and features music, dance and theatre.
[src:alderney/alderney] The Alderney Literary Festival began in March 2015, with talks and events relating to historical fiction and non-fiction.
[src:alderney/alderney] It is organised by the Alderney Literary Trust.
[src:alderney/alderney] In April 2011, sculptor Andy Goldsworthy completed a project called Alderney Stones, commenced in 2008, in which 11 large dried-earth spheres were placed at different sites on the island.
[src:alderney/alderney] The intention is that each stone will gradually erode, at different speeds depending on the location, and in some cases revealing objects buried inside.
[src:alderney/alderney] Materials included clay, earth, chain, old work gloves, bricks, hawser, wheat, wire, blackberries, poppy seeds and tools.
[src:alderney/alderney] Previously there was a school called Ormer House Preparatory School which closed in December 2013.
[src:alderney/alderney] There are several flights each day from Southampton and Guernsey, with links to many parts of the United Kingdom and Europe.
[src:alderney/alderney] Aurigny serves the island with Dornier 228s.
[src:alderney/alderney] Boats sail regularly between the island and France, and to the other Channel Islands.
[src:alderney/alderney] Manche Iles Express operates a high-speed passenger ferry in summer to Diélette in the commune of Flamanville, Manche in France, and to St Peter Port, Guernsey.
[src:alderney/alderney] Two boats offer seasonal service to Guernsey.
[src:alderney/alderney] A 12-passenger boat operates services to Cherbourg Harbour, Sark and St Peter Port.
[src:alderney/alderney] Alderney is 72.5 miles (116.7 kilometres) from St Malo and 70.3 miles (113.1 kilometres) from Poole.
[src:alderney/alderney] There are boat trips, water-taxi services and water and fuel access to visiting yacht crews.
[src:alderney/alderney] The busiest time is during the peak months of June, July and August as nearly 30,000 yacht crew members visit this harbour every year.
[src:alderney/alderney] Because of the island's size, vehicular transport is often unnecessary, although taxis, cars and bicycles are used.
[src:alderney/alderney] The Alderney Railway is the only remaining railway in the Channel Islands; it gives a timetabled public service, with scheduled trains to the lighthouse during the summer and special occasions such as Easter and Christmas.
[src:alderney/alderney] There is an occasional bus service around the island.
[src:alderney/alderney] Alderney allows people to ride motorbikes and mopeds without helmets and drive cars without seatbelts, but it is compulsory for those under 18 to wear helmets.
[src:alderney/alderney] The international vehicle registration code is *GBA*.
[src:alderney/alderney] As in the rest of the Bailiwick of Guernsey, mopeds and motorbikes with an engine of 50cc or less can be driven from the age of 14 with a provisional licence.
[src:alderney/alderney] The Alderney Water Board is responsible for the supply of water on the island.
[src:alderney/alderney] Water is sourced from bore holes and streams and is treated and stored at Corblets Quarry and Battery Quarry.
[src:alderney/alderney] Electricity was first supplied on Alderney in 1934 by Mr.
[src:alderney/alderney] The supply concession was transferred to Alderney Light and Power Company in 1939, which came under the control of the States of Guernsey Electricity Department, before reverting to the States of Alderney in 1950.
[src:alderney/alderney] Supplies from a new power station operated by Alderney Electricity Limited started on 1 April 1952.
[src:alderney/alderney] Electricity is generated by fuel oil driven generators.
[src:alderney/alderney] There are 3 × 2,000 kW, 2 × 50 kW and 2 × 450 kW engine generators.
[src:alderney/alderney] As of 2020, there are currently plans to develop tidal power and to construct a 220 kilometre France-Alderney-Britain cable link.
[src:alderney/alderney] The Alderney Voluntary Fire Brigade has a crew of 12 volunteer firefighters, and operates one Iveco Daily light water tender with a 10.5 m ladder, two Iveco water carriers each with a capacity of 4,500 litres, one Ford Ranger rapid response unit and two trailer units.
[src:alderney/alderney] A new fire station was officially opened on 20 October 2004 by Lt.-General Sir John Foley, the Lieutenant Governor of Guernsey.
[src:alderney/alderney] The fire station is near Braye Harbour, has four appliance bays, a workshop, kit room, mess and a training room, and achieves an average response time of nine minutes.
[src:alderney/alderney] The Alderney Airport Fire and Rescue Service is sometimes called on to help with larger conflagrations.
[src:alderney/alderney] In 2020, the Ambulance service merged into the Fire service to form the first combined fire and ambulance service in the British Isles outside of Dublin.
[src:alderney/alderney] Until 2020, the St John Alderney Ambulance Service operated the ambulance service on the island, and was staffed by volunteers.
[src:alderney/alderney] It had served Alderney since 1952 and was registered as a private company.
[src:alderney/alderney] Patients are transferred to the Mignot Memorial Hospital in St Anne, and any having major complications are then transferred to Guernsey or Southampton by the Aurigny between 7 am and 7 pm on an emergency basis.
[src:alderney/alderney] Outside these hours or in the event of bad weather preventing an air evacuation the transfer is achieved with the aid of the RNLI lifeboat service.
[src:alderney/alderney] Because of Alderney's low crime rate, day-to-day policing of Alderney is provided by a team of five locally based officers from the Guernsey Police, consisting of a sergeant in charge, two constables, and two special constables.
[src:alderney/alderney] They are regularly assisted by visiting constables from Guernsey.
[src:alderney/alderney] The Alderney lifeboat station was established in 1869, was closed in 1884, and was re-established in 1985 by the RNLI.
[src:alderney/alderney] Search and rescue services are provided by Channel Islands Air Search, which uses a Britten-Norman Islander to search large areas of water using infrared cameras and a number of other technologies.
[src:alderney/alderney] Formed in 1980, it is staffed entirely by volunteers and is based in Guernsey.
[src:alderney/alderney] When a major search is underway, the French coastguard and the Royal Navy are often involved, co-ordinated by the Maritime Rescue Co-ordination Centre in Jobourg, France.
[src:alderney/gg] The domain is administered by Island Networks, who also administer the .je domain for neighbouring territory Jersey.
[src:alderney/gg] The domain was chosen as other possible codes were already allocated.
[src:alderney/gg] Nigel Roberts and Laurie Brown, co-founders of Island Networks, created the .gg and .je domains in 1996 by proposing them to Jon Postel of the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority.
[src:alderney/gg] In the late 2000s, there was an increase in usage of the domains by local companies, with there being about 10,000 .gg and .je domain names by 2009.
[src:alderney/gg] Multiple video games, streamers and esports websites use Guernsey's domain (.gg) because "gg" is a common initialism used in multiplayer video games as an abbreviation for the phrase "good game", usually said at the end of a match.
[src:alderney/gg] For example, the VoIP application Discord, commonly used with multiplayer games, uses the domain discord.gg as a redirect to their main website, discord.com, as well as for Discord server invite links.
